<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Implement Food Security Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
is to implement a food security program in its poorest provinces,
Agriculture and Land Affairs Minister Thoko Didiza said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ensuring that households have enough to eat remains a priority
for the government, the minister said while introducing debate on
her department's budget vote.
</P>
<P>
"All our policies, including those guiding land reform,
international trade and rural development must result in greater
availability and accessibility of food at the household level,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the food security program, in partnership with the
Food and Agriculture Organization, had two main components --
irrigation rehabilitation and diversification of crops.
</P>
<P>
This would improve the production capacity of subsistence
farmers and those with limited resources in the Northern Province,
Eastern Cape and KwazZulu-Natal, she said.
</P>
<P>
Didiza said the government remains committed to "delivering" 30
percent of agricultural land to black people. So far, only 0.6
percent of it has been transferred "but we have made some dents",
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
