<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Clash in South Nigeria Kills 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-five persons have been
killed since Tuesday night in the recrudesced community clash
between the towns of Ife and Modakeke in Nigeria's southern Osun
State, official news agency said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN), the death toll
during the clash starting from March 3 between the two Yoruba
communities has amounted to 75.
</P>
<P>
Although the state government had since last week imposed a
dusk-to-dawn curfew on the troubled area, combatants took the
advantage of the poor logistics of the police for rekindling the
fighting during which both parties of the clash wantonly maimed
and killed people as well as torched houses.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the violence, which had killed 50 by
Tuesday, is due to a land dispute between the two Yoruba
communities.
</P>
<P>
More and more residents in Ife and Modakeke, both of which are
inhabited by Yorubas, one of the three main ethnic groups in
Nigeria, have been fleeing from the troubled towns to nearby areas
including the country's economic hub Lagos State.
</P>
<P>
The residents of the two towns have a long-standing rivalry
over the land ownership and political supremacy in the area that
has sporadically led to violence since 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
