<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Muslims Pray for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Moslems including
Lagos State Governor Bola Tinubu Thursday prayed for peace in the
country's economic capital Lagos to mark the Islamic holy holiday
of Eid-el-kabir.
</P>
<P>
At the Obalende praying ground in Lagos, Chief Imam of Lagos
State Alhaji Ibrahim urged Muslims in the state to maintain peace
and learn to tolerate people of other religions.
</P>
<P>
He reminded them of the need to live in accordance with the
dictates of the holy Quoran, which exhorts them to help the poor
and avoid ostentation.
</P>
<P>
He also cautioned the Muslims against spreading unfounded
reports which, he said, had led to various crises in the country
in the past.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between Moslems and Christians in the country's
northern State of Kaduna and some southeast states over the
introduction of Islamic Sharia law last month killed about 1,000
people.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian population is almost evenly divided between Moslems
and Christians. Most of the Christians are living in the southern
area of the country, including Lagos.
</P>
<P>
But as the biggest city and former capital of the West African
nation, Lagos also enjoys a large Moslem population.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the prayer, Tinubu put co-existence
between different religion faithfuls as a panacea for the
country's corporate existence and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The governor's wife, Remi Tinubu, a Christian, also said at the
occasion that she was at the praying ground to show solidarity
with Muslims in the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
