<HEADLINE> Rwandan Government Identifies Priorities of Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
identified decentralization, participatory justice and economic
development as the priority areas for its work, Rwanda News Agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Decentralization is important for good governance to be
attained and for encouraging participation of all in the
leadership and in the management of their own society," Minister
of Local Government Nyandwi Desire was quoted as saying at a
two-day seminar which brought together all prefects in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The government is continuing with the policy of decentralizing
power to the population and elections of consultative and
executive committees at prefectural and communal levels will take
place in September this year, Desire said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "participatory justice has to be applied for unity
and reconciliation to be attained."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of Agriculture, Livestock and Forestry
Ephraim Kabaija noted that "over 90 percent of Rwanda's population
depends on agriculture hence the need to develop the sector."
</P>
<P>
"Rwandans should learn how to manage the limited resources for
survival and should avoid depending on foreign assistance," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
