<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes U.S. Move to Ease Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Friday welcomed the U.S.
move to ease sanctions as "positive" and said that Tehran would
respond by importing U.S. grain and medicine.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome (the U.S move to allow) exports of Iranian
foodstuffs and carpets to the U.S. and see it as positive," Iranian
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the official Islamic Republic News Agency as
saying that "in response to this, the U.S. will be able to export
grain and medicine to" Iran.
</P>
<P>
Asefi was reacting to a speech by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to the American-Iranian Council in Washington
earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, Albright announced that the U.S. Administration
would allow Americans to purchase and import Iran's non-oil goods
such as carpets, dried fruits, nuts and caviar, a move seen as the
boldest attempt yet by the Clinton administration to try to improve
relations with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Foreign Ministry would make further
necessary response after conducting a comprehensive study on
Albright's speech.
</P>
<P>
"There were positive and negative points in this speech, on the
one hand past accusations were repeated, but on the other the U.S.
secretary of state has tried to admit America's past mistakes and
present a new and different attitude toward the Islamic Republic of
Iran."
</P>
<P>
In her speech, Albright wished the Iranian people a happy new
year and added: "Surely, the time has come for America and Iran to
enter a new season in which mutual trust may grow and the quality
of warmth supplant the long cold winter of our mutual discontent."
</P>
<P>
However, she reiterated U.S. allegations that Iran sponsors
terrorism, seeks weapons of mass destruction and persecutes
religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. move indicated a shift in Washington's policies, which
came after Iranian reformists won an overwhelming victory in the
parliamentary elections last month over the powerful conservatives,
who dominate the country's most important organs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Iran severed relations in 1980 following the
takeover of the U.S. embassy in Tehran by fervent Iranian students
in the heydays of the Islamic revolution, which toppled the former
pro-U.S. shah's regime.
</P>
<P>
The two countries tuned down their hostilities against each
other after President Mohammad Khatami, who came to power in 1997,
called for people-to-people contacts to bring down the "wall of
mistrust".
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been trying to export grains to Iran, but Iran
insisted that the U.S. should allow the flow of Iranian goods to
American markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
