<HEADLINE> Brazil to Increase Exports This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Foreign Minister
Luiz Felipe Lampreia forecast Friday that his country will
increase the volume of its exports as much as 20 percent this year,
if the world trade rises 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia said this at a seminar organized by the Brazilian
Finance Executives Institute, adding that the resuming of the
World Trade Organization discussions for the elimination of
protectionism for agriculture and textile products could bring
positive results for the Brazilian balance of trade.
</P>
<P>
He said that the assuming of the new U.S. president will make
easier the negotiations for the Free Trade Area of the Americas (
FTAA).
</P>
<P>
Lampreia said that the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) member
countries are ready for the negotiations and for the full
participation of Chile.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian foreign minister said his country wants to start
negotiations about the free trade agreement between Mercosur and
South Africa no later than two months from now.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia, who made last month an official visit to South Africa
last month, will present a document to the Mercosur ministers.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur is composed by Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay
and Chile and Bolivia as associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
