<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Vows to Stick to Lusaka Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
Friday reiterated his country's dedicated commitment to the Lusaka
cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference Friday evening after talking with
Belgian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs
Louis Michel that he would contribute to the work for the peaceful
settlement of the conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC).
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace accord is the most instrumental tool for
resolving the DRC issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
"All ideas now are around the implementation of the Lusaka
agreement. We cannot bring ideas which depart from the agreement,"
he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Museveni refuted reports that Ugandan
troops deployed in eastern DRC are creating provinces there.
</P>
<P>
Michel, who was heading a 22-member delegation to Uganda, said
that he talked with leaders of the DRC, Angola and Zimbabwe before
coming to Uganda early Friday morning and all those he talked with
promised to honor the Lusaka agreement.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, which has been backing the rebels in the DRC, sent
troops to the DRC in 1998 to allegedly protect its borders.
</P>
<P>
President of the DRC Laurent Kabila, however, has been accusing
Kampala of invading his country and looting its minerals, which
Uganda has vehemently denied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
