<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass Education Is Way Out for Uganda: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
Friday described mass education as the only way out for Uganda
which is suffering from high illiteracy rate and brain drain.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a graduation ceremony of Makerere University
students, the president said that the past education system was an
elite education system which provided opportunities only for the
very few.
</P>
<P>
Now education of the whole population should be stressed
because it is the only way to push Uganda forward, he said.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, who is also the chancellor of the university, urged
for improvement in policy, physical and infrastructural
developments because more students would step into the university
gate.
</P>
<P>
As a result of a Universal Primary Education (UPE) program
launched in 1997, Uganda's primary school enrolment has now more
than doubled to a total of 6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
At the function, Museveni also pledged to continue to provide
funding for very bright students from poor families. The
government would continue to sponsor some university students as
before, he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 students got their degrees or diplomas at the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Makerere University is famous for its graduates. Former
Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere and some other regional leaders
once studied in the university. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Scientists to Join in Mars Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian scientists are working to
contribute to future flights to the Mars in 2001, 2002 and 2007,
the country's Middle East News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Those missions, aiming to learn more about the red planet, will
be carried out in cooperation with U.S. National Aeronautics and
Space Administration (NASA) and the International Society for
Planet Discoveries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will contribute to the 2001 mission with a driller, to be
attached to a spaceship that NASA is expected to launch at that
time.
</P>
<P>
The driller, at a total cost of 1 million Egyptian pounds (289,
900 U.S. dollars), is being designed by Egyptian experts from both
scientific research and military production ministries.
</P>
<P>
It will be first tested in the Western Desert, which is similar
to Mars in biological makeup, climate, temperature and dust storms.
No more details were available yet concerning the other two future
flights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EP Calls for Equal Rights for Same-Sex Couples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Parliament on
Friday adopted a resolution urging the 15 European Union member
states to grand equal rights to same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
The European legislators approved the resolution with a vote of
265 for, 125 against with 33 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, passed in a European Parliament session in
Strasbourg, said that the EU nations should guarantee same-sex
couples rights equal to those enjoyed by traditional couples,
particularly as regards tax law, pecuniary rights and social
rights.
</P>
<P>
Some EU nations like Belgium, Denmark, the Netherlands and
Sweden already have granted legal recognition to extramarital
couples.
</P>
<P>
The EP resolution said that European citizens continue to
suffer discrimination and disadvantages in their personal and
professional life as a result of their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam Treaty, the basic treaty of the European Union,
has stipulated specific references against discrimination against
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament said that it noted with satisfaction
that Britain is amending its laws to allow homosexuals to follow
military careers though some others still ban homosexual relations
in the army.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called on the 13 countries now applying for
EU membership to ensure equal rights for homosexuals. The 13
countries are Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Slovenia,
Estonia, Cyprus, Romania, Slovakia, Latvia, Lithuania, Bulgaria,
Malta and Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
