<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Begins Talks with Cambodia on Khmer Rouge Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. team had begun
talks with the Cambodian delegation on the trial of the former
leaders of Khmer Rouge, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said the Cambodian delegation is headed by First
Minister Sok An.
</P>
<P>
The talks were "concentrated" and they would continue on
Saturday, the spokesman said
</P>
<P>
The 7-member team, led by Hans Corell, Under-Secretary-General
and the Legal Counsel, arrived in Cambodia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Corell, the delegation include: Ralph Zacklin,
assistant-Secretary-General and the deputy of the team; Lakhan
Mehrotra, head of the Jakarta office of the U.N. Transitional
Administration in East Timor; Shashi Tharoor, a director in Annan'
s office; John Renninger, who heads the Asia and pacific division
of the U.N. Department of Political Affairs; Daphna Shraga, a
senior officer in the U.N.office of Legal Affairs; and Mark
Quarterman, an officer in the Department of Political Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and Cambodia have been at odds over who would
be in control of a tribunal to try the former Khmer Rouge leaders.
</P>
<P>
U.N. legal experts are concerned that Cambodia's legal system
is too weak to guarantee justice on its own.
</P>
<P>
This will be the final round of negotiations and an agreement
with the Cambodia's Government is expected to be reached to ensure
a credible trial that meets minimum international standard.
</P>
