<HEADLINE> Uganda to Close 10 Diplomatic Missions Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
decided to temporarily close 10 of its 26 diplomatic missions
abroad due to inadequate funding, said the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs in a press release issued Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The affected embassies or high commissions are those in Abuja
and Cairo in Africa; Bonn, Paris, Rome and Moscow in Europe;
Beijing and Tokyo in Asia; and Ottawa and Havana in the America,
the release said.
</P>
<P>
"Government wishes to reassure all our friends and the general
public that this move will not, and indeed is not intended to
either affect or diminish our bilateral relations with the
countries where these missions are located," it said.
</P>
<P>
The affected missions would be covered from the nearest
diplomatic missions still operating and honorary consuls would be
appointed in those various capitals to look after the commercial
and consular interests of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan First Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign
Affairs Eriya Kategaya told a parliamentary committee Thursday
that this reduction was just geared at cutting down the costs.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports of embarrassment of Uganda's diplomats
abroad due to lack of fund to pay for accommodation or utilities.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni last October directed the country's
Foreign Ministry to close down all missions abroad except six.
</P>
<P>
There are now about 130 Ugandans working for diplomatic
missions abroad. The government's annual budget for the missions
is 10 million U.S. dollars, only 60 percent of the amount they
really need. 
</P>
</TEXT>
