<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Pilgrims Start Stoning of Devil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.7 million Saudi
and foreign pilgrims on Friday continued their pilgrimage, or Hajj
rituals by starting symbolic "stoning of the devil" in Mina,
ritual site in the holy city of Mecca in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The stoning ritual will last for three days and each pilgrim
will throw seven pebbles at each of the three different pillars
symbolizing the devil as a sign of the human being overcoming the
devil.
</P>
<P>
After this rite pilgrims will return to the Grand Mosque in
Mecca to complete the last part of their Hajj journey by performing
circumvention around the holy Kaaba, which according to Koran is
the oldest house of worship in the world.
</P>
<P>
This year's Hajj rituals began on Tuesday, with nearly 2.3
million pilgrims from around the Moslem world took part in
Tuesday's 11-kilometer procession from Mecca to Mina.
</P>
<P>
The ritual in Mina is called the Day of Al-Tarwiya, a word used
in the days of the Prophet Mohammad for stocking enough water for
the journey to Mount Arafat and the Valley of Mozdalifa.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims spent their night in Mina on Tuesday in the 40,000
fire-proof tents erected by the Saudi government with a total cost
of 2.4 billion riyals (640 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the pilgrims climbed Mount Arafat, where Prophet
Mohammad delivered his final sermon 14 centuries ago. They spent
the day on the hill "praying for forgiveness and seeking the
blessings of God."
</P>
<P>
The Hajj is one of the five pillars of Islam and must be
performed by every able Moslem. The climbing of Mount Arafat is
considered as the most difficult stage, and the rituals on the hill
marks the climax of the annual pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
During a sermon on Mount Arafat, the pilgrims were told that
they will be as free of sin as newborns. They were also urged to
stand united and to cooperate with each other against enemies.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday evening, the pilgrims descended from Mount Arafat
and made their way, many on food, to the Valley of Mozdalifa, where
they picked up pebbles for the stoning ritual.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the pilgrims performed prayers of Eid Al-Adha, the
most important Islamic festival to slay and sacrifice sheep, cows
and camels to mark Abraham's readiness to sacrifice his son for
God.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Minister of Health Osama Ibn Abdel-Majid on Friday said
this year's pilgrimage season has so far been "free of epidemics
and that no security incidents or fires" were registered.
</P>
<P>
A tent fire caused by using gas cylinders during the 1997 Hajj
season killed more than 350 pilgrims and injured over 1,600 others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Pull out From Lebanon Completely: Peres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A scheduled Israeli troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon will be complete and Israel will not
retain any part of a border zone in Lebanon after the pullout,
Regional Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Peres made the remarks to visiting British journalist Patrick
Seale, biographer of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad. During their
meeting, Seale asked if Israel would, as reported in Israeli media,
keep parts of the border zone it occupied in southern Lebanon as
part of a unilateral withdrawal plan.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet on March 5 gave backing to a key pledge made
by Prime Minister Ehud Barak to withdraw from southern Lebanon by
July, with or without a peace deal with Syria, the main power in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Chief of Staff Lt.-Gen. Shaul Mofaz presented Barak on
Friday the military plan for a unilateral withdrawal, code-named "
Operation Morning Twilight," Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Another military plan for a withdrawal under the framework of a
peace agreement with Syria, which code-named "Operation New
Horizon," is also in the making.
</P>
<P>
Both plans deal with measures to reinforce Israeli defense after
a pullout from Lebanon. Israeli media said recently that if Israel
has to carry out the "Operation Morning Twilight," or a unilateral
withdrawal, it might keep some military outposts in the buffer zone
in areas about 500 meters north of the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out the 15-kilometer-deep border zone in Lebanon
in 1985 with a self-claimed aim of preventing cross-border
guerrilla attacks on its north. But mounting Israeli casualties
have spurred a growing public pressure for a pullout.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks, which resumed last December
after a four-year break, broke off in January over a dispute on the
fate of the Golan Heights, a strategic Syrian plateau seized by
Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Defense Minister Mustafa Tlass said Thursday that the
United States would succeed in bringing the sides back to the
negotiating table "within weeks."
</P>
<P>
But both Israeli and U.S. officials said they were not aware of
any imminent announcement of negotiations restarting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
