<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges N. Parties to Make Concessions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Life is fleeting and opportunities come and go. We have the
chance of a lifetime. Whatever the differences, it's not worth
another life, not one. It's not worth another day's delay,"
Clinton told a gala dinner attended by the Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams
and David Trimble of the Ulster Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the statement before holding five separate
meetings Friday and hosting a St. Patrick's Day reception at the
White House. Thursday's dinner was hosted by the America Ireland
Fund and joined by more than 1,000 guests.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told the guests that he was proud of the supporting
role he had played in the peace process, adding that the cease-
fires now are measured in years, not weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I must confess as your friend that I still do not know the
answers," he said, expressing his regrets that the peace process
is in a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told a
regular briefing that the administration did not expect any
breakthrough during Friday's meetings.
</P>
<P>
"I'd say that this is more than just courtesy, but I also don't
anticipate any breakthrough. There are discussions scheduled for
when they return home, and they will continue to try to find a way
through to implementing the Good Friday accords," Lockhart added.
</P>
<P>
The Good Friday accords were signed by the parties involved in
the future of the British province of Northern Ireland in 1998.
The peace process runs into an impasse after the Irish Republic
Army (IRA) refused to disarm and Britain suspended the self-rule
in the province.
</P>
<P>
Major players in the Northern Irish peace process, including
Adams, British Secretary of State for Northern Ireland Peter
Mandelson, Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern and pro-Britain
Trimble, are gathering here. 
