<HEADLINE> European Airlines Complain Over Airport Switch Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission got on
Friday a complaint filed by 12 European airlines blaming Italy's
plan to switch their flights from Linate to Malpensa.
</P>
<P>
The complaint was the latest move by the airlines in their
fight with Italian authorities who wanted to switch airlines other
than those of Italian origin from the more popular airport to the
newly-constructed airport.
</P>
<P>
A decree drawn by Italian Transport Minister Pierluigi Bersani
enforcing the switch plan is to come into force on April 20. The
Italian government argued that the switch is needed to reduce the
pressure of overcrowdedness on Linate.
</P>
<P>
Malpensa is 53 kilometers away from downtown Milan and ground
transportation would affect the passenger flow with the airlines
having to use the new airport.
</P>
<P>
The 12 airlines said that the switch plan unfairly
discriminates against them in favor of Italy's national carrier
Alitalia.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, has required the Italian authorities to modify the switch
plan from Linate to Malpensa.
</P>
<P>
The airlines complaining against the switch plan include
British Airways, Lufthansa, Air France, Sabena SA, Finnair,
Scandinavian Airlines System, Maersk Air, Olympic Airways, Iberia,
TAP Air Portugal, Austrian Airlines and Aer Lingus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
