<HEADLINE> Rwanda Denies U.N. Report on Involvement in UNITA Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda Friday denied the
allegations by a U.N. report that its authorities played a role in
aiding the rebel National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) to circumvent U.N. sanctions by illegally selling
gems for weapons.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Mutaboba, the Rwandan permanent representative to the
United Nations, told a press conference here that his government
has nothing to do with military cooperation with UNITA, arranging
diamond sales for UNITA, and facilitating UNITA meeting with
weapon brokers, as alleged by a report of the Security Council
Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
"The Rwandan Government wishes to state categorically that
these allegations have no foundation, and are merely hearsay from
quarters that distort facts for reasons known to themselves," he
said.
</P>
<P>
 "When the Panel of Experts visited Rwanda, it was given
information and explanations which are not reflected in the final
report for reasons unknown to us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda is one of a dozen of countries singled out by the
report, which, compiled by the U.N. Sanction Committee headed by
Ambassador Robert Fowler of Canada, spells out how UNITA has been
able to sidestep U.N. sanctions by buying weapons, mainly from
Bulgaria, having them shipped to African nations and paying for
them with diamonds from mines it controls.
</P>
<P>
Primarily, the report accuses President Blaise Compaoro of
Burkina Faso, President Gnassingbe Eyadema of Togo and the late
Zairian dictator Mobutu Sese Seko of having personally received
diamonds for having helped UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi with arms
and fuel shipments in violations of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Burkina Faso, Togo, Rwanda and Bulgaria have denied the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council imposed an arms and fuel embargo on UNITA
in 1993, a year before the United Nations brokered a peace
agreement between the rebels and government. In 1998, six months
before the peace agreement collapsed, the Council expanded the
measures to include a ban on rebel diamond exports, which are
estimated to have supplied the group with up to 4 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"There is no military cooperation with UNITA," he said. "The
fact that Rwandan troops used the Angolan territory to evacuate
Rwandan troops did not necessarily mean a pact with (Jonas)
Savimbi," who is the leader of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
"Angola knows how we evacuated our troops in a rescue
military operation," he said. "Nobody ever had contact with
Savimbi or any UNITA officials for that matter."
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no grain of truth in the allegations that
Rwanda 'have allowed UNITA to operate more or less freely in
Kigali for the purpose of arranging diamond sales,'" he aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
