<HEADLINE> Private Nazi Photo Collection Unearthed in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian history professor has
unearthed a private collection of photographs chronicling the rise
of the Nazi party at a second-hand store in Sudbury, southern
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
The album includes pictures of Hitler, Herman Goering, minister
of the interior, Heinrich Himmler, head of the SS, and propaganda
minister Josef Goebels, the Ottawa Citizen newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
There are also photos of the wedding of a ranking Nazi party
member, where 14 ushers in army uniforms give the Seig Heil salute,
forming an arch outside the church, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very impressed by some of these earlier pictures that show
the honor guard for Hitler and the access the photographer had to
them,"professor Dieter Buse of Laurentian University was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The collection of pictures taken in the 1930s must have been a
job by someone trusted "within the security ring" of the Nazi
party, said the professor.
</P>
<P>
"What makes this interesting" is that Nazi leader Adolf Hitler
had only one official photographer -- Heinrich Hoffman, the
professor said, adding Hitler and Hoffman often scrutinized
pictures together,selecting the ones for public distribution.
</P>
<P>
Tory Cameron, owner of the TNT Second Hand Store in Sudbury,
said he purchased the private collection from a local resident
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said the seller was in his late 30s and not of German
descent.He had no idea how the collection ended up in the hands of
the seller,the store owner said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
