<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Government Launches Campaign for Bilateral Accords with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government has launched
a campaign to win support for Switzerland's bilateral accords with
the European Union (EU) ahead of a referendum in May.
</P>
<P>
The campaign to win over Switzerland's voters to the idea of
closer ties with the European Union started Friday with the launch
of two websites, run by the ministries of economics and foreign
affairs,according to Swiss Radio International.
</P>
<P>
The government has given itself two months to sell the
bilateral accords to the public before a referendum scheduled on
May 21.
</P>
<P>
The two websites are published in German and French. They
explain how important the EU is to Switzerland, and they give
users the chance to put questions or opinions to the government.
</P>
<P>
The site reminds voters that Switzerland is an integral part of
Europe, both geographically and in terms of trade. It points out
that the EU is Switzerland's most important trading partner, and
that future Swiss prosperity depends on relations with Europe.
</P>
<P>
Surveys suggest that the bilateral accords have the support of
the majority of Swiss voters. But, equally, many remain deeply
skeptical about closer ties with Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
