<HEADLINE> Top German CDU Officials Charged With Bribery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- German state prosecutors said on
Friday that they had charged a top aide to former German
Chancellor Helmit Kohl and a fugitive arms dealer in connection
with the Christian Democratic Union's massive finance scandal.
</P>
<P>
Former CDU's treasurer Walter Leisler Kiep and arms dealer
broker Karlheinz Schreiber had been charged in a case of bribery,
said Augsburg Judge Maximilian Hofmeister. But he refused to
provide with any details about charges in 165-page indictment.
</P>
<P>
Kiep was once the CDU treasurer from 1971 to 1992.Helmut Kohl
was the chairman of the CDU from 1973 to 1998 and German
Chancellor from 1982 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
Karlheinz Schreiber gave the CDU one million marks (493,000 U.
S. dollars) in 1991 in handover at a Swiss parking lot. The cash
was packed in briefcase and was taken by Kiep and former CDU
finance advisor, Horst Weyrauch.
</P>
<P>
Schreiber offered a bribe to officials of Kohl's government in
order to sell 36 Fox light tanks to Saudi Arabia, but all members
of Kohl's government denied it firmly.
</P>
<P>
Schreiber has fled to Canada. Germany wants to extradite him.
</P>
</TEXT>
