<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torrential Rains Flood Central Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains in central
Mozambique have led to further flooding in Sofala province,
Mozambique News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Buzi river burst its banks again, once more flooding the
Buzi town. About 7,000 people, who ventured back to the town
earlier this month when the waters subsided, had to return to the
accommodation centres set up by the government for flood victims.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, two small boats are being used to
rescue people who have suddenly found themselves stranded in the
outlying suburbs of Buzi, and in the locality of Guaraguara.
</P>
<P>
The flooding in the Buzi valley is likely to worsen since the
Chicamba dam on the river's main tributary, the Revue, has been
forced to open its floodgates, discharging 400 cubic meters of
water a second, the report said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the continuing rains, it is not yet possible to
repair the main north-south highway in the Sofala district of
Chibabava. About 500 meters of the road is now under water that
is up to 1.5 meters deep. The road state is worsening further
in southern province of Inhambane. In addition to earlier cuts in
Temane and Pambara, the road is now also under water in the
Vulanjane area. This is the same area where the road suffered
severe damage in the February 1999 floods.
</P>
<P>
Currently, no overland transport is possible from the
provincial capital city of Inhambane to the districts of
Vilanculo, Inhassoro and Govuro.
</P>
<P>
Nova Mambone, the capital of the Govuro district, is in danger
of further flooding as the Save river rises again. A helicopter
carrying relief goods to this town failed to land on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With the road destroyed, Inhambane and Gaza provinces can no
longer be supplied with fuel and other basic necessities by trucks
from Beira, the capital of Sofala province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
