<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Revive Education for Disabled People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government is set to
revive education trends for physically and mentally disabled
children and adults, Rwandan News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Narcisse Musabeyezu, director of nursery and primary school in
the Ministry of Education and coordinator for disabled education,
made the remarks during a two-day workshop in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Musabeyezu said: "Parents and teachers need to understand their
role in the education of the disabled, formulate modalities for
the establishment of a system that cares and caters for the
handicapped and suggest measures and recommendations for the
improvement of their status in society."
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Education Jean Damasce ne
Ntawukuriryayo, "although education is considered as a right, the
mentally and physically handicapped have not always been
integrated into the system".
</P>
<P>
Rwanda has over 5000 traumatized people following the 1994
genocide, who need trained counsellors to rectify the trauma.
</P>
<P>
Participants found it imperative to have trained teachers in
the matters related to special education needs of the handicapped.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
