<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Aluminium Terminal Put Into Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An Australian ship carrying 6,300
tons of raw material for the production of aluminium is for the
first time moored in the Matola aluminium terminal at Maputo port,
Mozambique News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The terminal itself, built in partnership between Mozal, the
company that owns the aluminium smelter being built on the
outskirts of Maputo, and the Mozambican publicly owned ports and
railway company, CFM, was inaugurated on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration ceremony, David Nunro, director of
 Billiton, the London-based metals company that holds 47 percent
of Mozal's shares, said that the building of the smelter is about
80 percent complete and the first ingot of aluminium should be
cast by the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
This means that the factory will have been built in just 26
months and, according to Nunro, it will cost less than 1.3 billion
U.S. dollars estimated initially.
</P>
<P>
"The terminal that we are inaugurating on Thursday was
projected to receive ships with a capacity of 35,000 tons," he
said, adding that "at this terminal 40 ships a year will moor,
carrying 500,000 tons of alumina and 92,000 tons of coke, at a
combined value of 120 million U.S. dollars."
</P>
<P>
The terminal has three silos to store raw materials, the
largest of which, for alumina, has a capacity of 45,000 tons. The
other two silos can store up to 11,000 tons of coke.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the name of the Mozambican government, Transport
Minister Tomas Salomao described the terminal as a good example of
partnership between national companies represented by CFM and
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
For the building of the terminal, Mozal contributed 13 million
U.S. dollars, which CFM is to pay back through the funds generated
by the port services rendered to Mozal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
