<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Up 0.5 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices surged 0.
5 percent in February, the biggest jump in 10 months, led by a
record increase in fuel oil prices and sharply higher gasoline
costs, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The big advance in the Consumer Price Index, the nation's
broadest gauge of inflation, followed a modest 0.2 percent rise in
January, and was slightly worse than the 0.4 percent gain forecast
by many analysts.
</P>
<P>
Last month's increase stemmed from a huge 4.6 percent jump in
energy prices, the biggest gain since a 6 percent rise in April.
</P>
<P>
The 0.5 percent increase in overall consumer prices also was
the steepest increase since April, when consumer prices rose by 0.
7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Excluding volatile energy and food components, the "core" rate
of inflation rose a mild 0.2 percent in February after a matching
gain in January. February's core rate was right on target with
many analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
Friday's report comes one day after the government said
inflation at the wholesale level, led by huge increases in home
heating oil, gasoline and other energy costs, jumped 1 percent in
February, the biggest one-month surge in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department said the CPI for the past three months
implied an annual rate of inflation of 3.9 percent, a figure
likely to weigh on Federal Reserve policymakers who meet next
Tuesday to consider monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The Fed has raised interest rates four times since last June,
and has made clear it will gradually raise rates further to cool
the U.S. economy and attempt to head off inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
In Friday's report, the government said the rise in overall
energy prices in February was led by a whopping 34.6 percent gain
in fuel oil prices, an all-time monthly high. Gasoline prices rose
6.3 percent, the largest gain since April. Natural gas prices went
up by 1.7 percent, the biggest rise since September, and
electricity rose 0.8 percent, the largest increase July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Food prices, meanwhile, rose a sizable 0.4 percent, the largest
increase since October 1998. Rising prices for beef, pork and
fresh fruits more than offset falling prices for poultry and fresh
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
February's data also showed strong price rises elsewhere.
Housing prices gained 0.5 percent, the largest gain since January
of 1991 when it posted a 0.8 percent rise. Transportation prices,
a sector affected by higher gasoline costs, rose 1.3 percent, the
largest rise since April's 2.4 percent increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
