<HEADLINE> Britain Applauds German Lifting of British Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Friday welcomed Germany
's decision to lift a ban imposed on imports of British beef after
outbreaks of mad cow disease and called on France to do the same.
</P>
<P>
"All credit to the Federal Government of Germany," British
Agriculture Minister Nick Brown said.
</P>
<P>
"I really do hope it has a knock-on effect. France is now
completely isolated on this issue within the EU...they really
should think again...they're defying the law," he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Farmers Union(NFU) also welcomed the decision.
</P>
<P>
"This was the right decision and leaves France conspicuously
out on a limb in Europe over its illegal ban. There is no possible
reason left for France to maintain its illegal ban," NFU President
Ben Gill said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Germany's upper house of parliament has voted on Friday by 39
votes to 30 to lift the country's four-year ban on imports of
British beef.
</P>
<P>
The ban was imposed in 1996 after scientists said they believed
mad cow disease, or bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), a
deadly,brain-wasting disorder for which there is no known cure,
could spread via infected meat from cattle to people.
</P>
<P>
Germany's decision follows legal moves by the European
Commission after Germany failed to comply with last year's
European Union agreement to reopen all beef markets.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission lifted its ban on British beef sales to
other EU countries last year after Britain introduced new rules on
raising and slaughtering cattle.
</P>
<P>
France retained its import ban, saying British safety measures
were not adequate. France is now the only EU member still banning
British beef imports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan to Launch Millennium Report On His Vision of U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N.Secretary-General Kofi
Annan will present a major statement on his vision for the world
body in a report to be launched on March 30, U.N. sources said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "We the Peoples: The United Nations in the
Twenty-first Century," is being prepared for a summit of heads of
State or government to be held at the United Nations this
September.
</P>
<P>
The report will set out a practical vision for the United
Nations in a globalized world, 55 years after the Organization was
founded.
</P>
<P>
Among its key concepts is the need to make globalization more
inclusive, to create more opportunities for all and not leave
entire continents and billions of people behind in squalor.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Millennium Summit of the United Nations, expected
to be the largest-ever gathering of heads of State or government,
will open on September 6 in New York.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations General Assembly designated its fifty-fifth
session, starting on September 5, as the Millennium Assembly, and
decided to hold the Summit in order to consider how the United
Nations can best meet the challenges of the new century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
