<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Voting for Russian Presidency Starts in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Early voting in Russia's
presidential elections began Friday morning in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya amid heightened security, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Federal servicemen stationed in remote mountainous areas of the
province or those on combat missions will be the first to cast
their ballots, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
"Special attention was paid to security -- of both voters and
election commission members," said Dzhamal Mezhidov, deputy
chairman of the Chechen Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
As Russia moves closer to the presidential elections scheduled
for next Sunday, rumors are rising in the breakaway republic that
the rebels could capture Grozny and Gudermes, the two largest
Chechen cities.
</P>
<P>
Intelligence reports suggest that "gang leaders are continuing
their efforts to thwart the Russian presidential elections in
Chechnya," Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the Kremlin spokesman on Chechnya,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police forces there have been placed on high alert as of
Thursday to cope with the increased threat, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
None of the 12 presidential candidates are campaigning in
Chechnya, although some action groups are expected to operate
there in support of acting President Vladimir Putin and Communist
Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, the two front runners.
</P>
<P>
For Moscow, presidential elections in Chechnya have special
political significance. A federal military campaign has been
raging there since last September to root out the rebels, who
staged two waves of armed incursions into neighboring Daghestan
and were allegedly behind a spate of apartment bombings that left
some 300 people dead in Moscow and two other Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
"Participation in the elections is important for us in Chechnya
as part of the (Russian) federation," said Mezhidov of the Chechen
Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
According to Lieutenant General Ivan Babichev, the military
commandant of the security zone in Chechnya, over 450,000 people
are expected to cast their votes in the province's 336 polling
stations, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Election officials have loosened requirements in the balloting
to facilitate the Chechen civilians with no passports. In order to
vote, it will be enough to produce a pensioner's card, a war
veteran's card or a certificate from the local administration,
Babichev said.
</P>
<P>
"We are giving everyone a chance to vote," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
