<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Court Turns Down Constitutional Amendments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Constitutional Court of
Mongolia has turned down an parliamentary act to amend the
constitution, Mongolian news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting of the court, with a
discussion focus on whether the amendments have violated the
constitution itself.
</P>
<P>
Some participants considered the amendments as a violation to
the constitution, saying they have infringed 20 provisions of the
Mongolian constitution. But some parliamentarians insisted that
the constitutional court doesn't have the right to discuss the
content of the amendments ratified by the parliament on December
20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The decision is to be discussed at a plenary meeting of the
parliament, and will be put into effect if accepted by the
majority of the parliament. Otherwise, the constitutional court
would have to call on another meeting involving more members.
</P>
</TEXT>
