<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Holy City" in Turkey Revamped for Christian Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Residents of a Christian "Holy
City" in northwestern Turkey are having their hands full preparing
the city for an influx of tourists to mark the 2000th anniversary
of Jesus Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
Iznik Municipality in the Bursa province is working on six
projects for restoration of historic sites and tourism promotion
which will cost nearly 100 billion Turkish liras (200,000 U.S.
dollars), local press reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Designated as a "Holy City" by the Christian world in the 1970s,
Iznik is rich in historic and religious works which date back to
the Roman, Byzantine, Seljukian and Ottoman periods.
</P>
<P>
Iznik Mayor Zeynel Abidin Turan said that initiatives have been
launched to introduce the historic and tourism assets of Iznik to
the world.
</P>
<P>
Turan said that 15 Orthodox leaders would gather in Iznik for a
Christmas ceremony on December 26, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Announces Measures to Liberalize Insurance Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS), the central bank, Friday unveiled measures to
liberalize the country's insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
In a press release MAS said with immediate effect it will lift
the closed-door policy on direct insurers and the 49 percent
shareholding restriction on foreign ownership in locally-owned
direct insurers.
</P>
<P>
MAS will also adopt an open market entry policy for new
insurance brokers and maintain the existing current open policy on
admission to reinsurers and captive insurers.
</P>
<P>
MAS underlined that the awarding of insurance licenses will be
subject to applicants who meet the admission criteria it has
established.
</P>
<P>
It also promised to introduce measures to raise standards of
corporate governance and market conduct in line with international
best practices and strengthen protection of policyholders'
interests by insurers.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization of the insurance industry in Singapore was first
introduced by Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong when
he stressed the need to liberalize, upgrade and modernize the
insurance industry in his key-note address at the 9th Pacific
Insurance Conference on August 16, 1999.
</P>
<P>
MAS said its objective in liberalizing entry to insurance
industry is to create a more vibrant and competitive industry,
with greater efficiency, choice of products and value to customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brussels Expected to Join European Bourse Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Brussels stock market is
expected to join at least two other European bourses next week to
create Europe's second largest bourse.
</P>
<P>
The performances of the local stock market were stimulated to a
high record this week by the talks between the Brussels stock
market and its Paris and Amsterdam counterparts on their merger.
</P>
<P>
After Wednesday's record rise in Brussels, the local stock
exchange enjoyed another heated run Thursday when the flagship Bel
20 index rose 6.79 percent to close at 2,906.66.
</P>
<P>
During the course of the day's trading, the index once rose by
as high as 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Finance Minister Didier Reynders said earlier this week
that a decision on the future of the Brussels stock market would
be made in the coming days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
He added that it would be good for the companies that are
listed on the Brussels stock market or considering a listing.
</P>
<P>
Should the merger of Brussels, Paris and Amsterdam bourses be
announced next Monday, they will combine to make the second
largest bourse in Europe behind London, with a total of 2,400
billion euro (about 2,326 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Bel 20 currently possesses a capitalization of 275 billion
Belgian francs (about 266.7 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
