<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europeans Urged to Prevent Children From Sex Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Lobbyists, lawyers, activists
and computer scientists gathered here on Friday to raise further
awareness to prevent children from sex abuse on computer networks.
</P>
<P>
An international forum was held here under the auspices of the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (
UNESCO), aimed at urging people to join the fight against
paedophilia on the Internet and to combat child pornography.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO launched a campaign known as Innocence in Danger to
ensure coordinated follow-up actions already taken by the European
countries in the fight against child pornography and paedophilia.
</P>
<P>
The campaign sought to group together Internet professionals
and jurists, child protection specialists, dignitaries and
political leaders from various countries to raise world awareness
and mobilize human, technical and financial resources for the
fight.
</P>
<P>
The Brussels forum was held three days before the trial of
Belgium's most notorious paedophile Marc Dutroux who was accused
of raping almost a dozen and killing at least two little girls in
the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The trial of Dutroux is scheduled for next Monday, almost four
years after he was arrested and two years after he broke loose
from guarding gendarmerie to run free for three hours and a half
in April 1998 before he was caught up again.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was sentenced to 13 years in jail in 1989 for raping
five girls but was released early and only to be arrested in
August 1996 after two girls were rescued from a dungeon in his
cellar.
</P>
<P>
Two bodies of little girls were found in his house and two more
bodies were discovered in that of one of his associates.
</P>
<P>
The exposure of Dutroux' crimes against little girls created a
furor in Belgium and across Europe. Some 350,000 people gathered
on the streets of the Belgian capital of Brussels in 1996 to
protest against the inefficiency of the country's police and
justice system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
