<HEADLINE> Kenya Issues Amnesty on Small Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
announced amnesty on Friday for those in possession of illegal
firearms if they surrender them to the authorities within a month
starting immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Those who surrender the illegal arms within this period will
not be persecuted," Moi said at a Baringo district leaders meeting
in central Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He said that arms could be handed over to district
commissioner's offices or nearby police stations, according to a
press release by the Presidential Press Service.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty came soon after the Conference on Proliferation of
Small Arms in Great Lakes Region and Horn of Africa ended in
Nairobi on Wednesday with a call for cooperation in curbing the
spread of illegal arms blamed for fueling violence and crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
