<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Keeps Support for Refugee Return to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said on
Friday that it would continue to support the return of refugees
and displaced people to Bosnia and Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The EU's Obnova 2000 integrated return program is designed to
provide financing of 50.1 million euro (about 48.5 million U.S.
dollars) for a package of measures to ensure sustainable return
movements.
</P>
<P>
Aid will be also provided for housing reconstruction and
rehabilitation of related infrastructure, income generation
measures, demining and measures to provide legal advice and
assistance to refugees and displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
The Obnova 2000 program will support breakthrough return
movements to previously closed municipalities in Bosnia, such as
Republika Srpska, and it will support regional return movements
from Croatia to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the EU, said
that a successful return process is fundamental for the creation
of a stable Bosnia and is one of the cornerstones of the Dayton
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The EU committed assistance funds of up to 1.3 billion euro (
about 1.2 billion dollars) to Bosnia between 1996 and 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Upper House Lifts Ban on British Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's upper house of the
parliament, the Bundesrat, on Friday lifted a national ban on
British beef.
</P>
<P>
British beef must be clearly labeled to protect consumers from
the possible risks of mad cow disease, or bovine spongiform
encephalopathy, said the Bundesrat.
</P>
<P>
Since the mad cow disease caused by the British beef began in
March 1996, almost all the countries of the European Union have
banned import of the British beef. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
