<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliament Passes Budget for Fiscal 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet, or parliament, on
Friday adopted a record-high 84.99 trillion yen (770.9 billion U.S.
dollars) national budget for fiscal year 2000, featuring measures
designed to spur sustainable recovery of the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The House of Councilors (upper house) passed the general-
account budget for the year starting from April 1 at a plenary
session, with the support of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (
LDP) and its two coalition partners, the Liberal Party (LP) and
the New Komeito party.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was submitted to parliament on January 28,
cleared the House of Representatives (lower house) on February 28.
</P>
<P>
The budget features a 2.6 percent expansion in general
expenditures to a record 48,091.4 billion yen (436.2 billion
dollars) for funding public works and other policy-oriented
projects.
</P>
<P>
The expansionary fiscal policy is designed to meet the Japanese
government's economic growth target of 1.0 percent in real terms
in fiscal 2000, which would be the second straight year of growth.
The government has voiced confidence that it will be able to
attain its goal of 0.6 percent growth for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
To help fund the budget, the Japanese government will have to
float a record 85.87 trillion yen (778.9 billion dollars) in bonds
during fiscal 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
