<HEADLINE> Int'l Symposium on Obesity to Be Held in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and foreign medical
specialists will hold a symposium next week in Beijing to discuss
how to deal with obesity, which is becoming a global health
problem.
</P>
<P>
The symposium will also focus on establishing new criterion for
the clinical diagnosis of overweight and obesity, the latest
weight-loss methods, and other health-related topics, according to
the event's organizer.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine estimate
that 14 percent of young and middle-aged urban Chinese are
overweight, and in some cities in north China, overweight people
make up nearly half of local population.
</P>
<P>
Another study has found that obesity among Chinese children has
grown at an annual rate of nine percent over the past decade,
indicating that the number of fat children will double in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Specialists warn of a possible sharp increase in the overweight
population in the coming years, and note that obesity may become
the primary health threat in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Obesity, which is often the result of an unhealthy diet and a
sedentary life, may lead to high blood pressure, cardiovascular
diseases, diabetes, and related complications, doctors say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
