<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Surplus Down to 65 Mln U.S. Dlrs in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine trade deficit, the
export-import gap, continued to drop to a surplus of 65 million U.
S. dollars in January from last year's 182 million dollars, the
government said Friday.
</P>
<P>
National Statistics Office (NSO) data shows that merchandise
exports increased by 5.3 percent to 2.7 billion dollars while
imports rose by 10.6 percent to 2.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
This brought total trade in goods between the Philippines and
the rest of the world to 5.4 billion dollars, up by 7.8 percent
from 4.98 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The country's purchases for electronics and components, with a
26.7 percent share, remained high which went up by 9.5 percent to
708.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by mineral fuels, lubricants and related
materials which went up by 8.5 percent to 250.2 million dollars
and telecommunication equipment valued at 210.01 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for 42.9 percent of the import bill, capital goods
was the top purchases for the month with aggregate payments
reaching 1.2 billion dollars which was 16.2 percent higher than
979.44 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Payments for raw materials and intermediate goods, meanwhile,
amounted to 1.01 billion dollars from 968.25 million dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
The NSO said the United States and Japan remained the biggest
sources of imports with sales amounting to 559.8 million dollars
and 467 million dollars respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
