<HEADLINE> Tight Security in Delhi Prior to Clinton Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Security went tighter in the
Indian capital on Friday with just two days left before U.S.
President Bill Clinton's arrival here for his south Asian tour.
</P>
<P>
Delhi police personnel and U.S. security officials were busy
fine-tuning various security measures, while the Plush Maurya
Sheraton Hotel, where Clinton would stay during his visit, was
sealed off on Friday morning by U.S. security men and armed guards
of Delhi police.
</P>
<P>
Fire safety system and communication networks in the hotel were
thoroughly checked and an anti-sabotage team of the Delhi police
was working overtime combing the hotel and its surrounding areas
for any possible explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
Several Police Control Room jeeps could be seen parking around
the hotel and policemen were keeping strict vigil on people moving
around in this sensitive area.
</P>
<P>
Close circuit televisions and security cameras have also been
installed in some "strategic parts" of the hotel, police sources
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to a deal between the Indians and the Americans, the
proximate security of Clinton will be solely managed by U.S.
security officials and the Delhi police would only provide "outer
ring" security cover, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Elaborate security arrangements have also been made at Rajghat,
where Clinton will pay homage to the Father of the Nation Mahatma
Gandhi, said Suresh Roy, joint commissioner of Delhi police.
</P>
<P>
"All security measures are being taken for (the) smooth and
peaceful visit of Clinton," said Roy, adding that the Delhi police
and the U.S. security agencies have maintained "close cooperation
and coordination."
</P>
<P>
According to reliable sources, security in and around the U.S.
embassy in Chanakyapuri area had also been beefed up in recent
days.
</P>
<P>
Delhi Police Commissioner Ajai Raj Sharma said Wednesday that
the entire Delhi police force, which has more than 55,000
personnel, had been mobilized and put on a "general state of alert
" to ensure "foolproof security" for the U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
Security measures already taken by the Delhi police force
included a close watch on the large number of Afghan refugees in
the capital and a constant vigil on the entry and exit points to
the city, said Sharma.
</P>
<P>
The police will also make sure that the Clinton visit would not
be disturbed by any possible protest actions, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
