<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Dependence on Food Imports Makes Singapore Vulnerable: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SINGAPORE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Heavy dependence on primary
food imports has made Singapore vulnerable to unforeseen
disruptions in food supplies and outbreak of food-poisoning and
zoonotic diseases, Singapore Minister for National Development Mah
Bow Tan told the parliament Friday.
</P>
<P>
He asked the parliament to take the move to restructure the
Primary Production Department (PPD) under his ministry into a
statutory board called the Agri-food and Veterinary Authority (AVA)
on April 1, 2000, and assign it a mandate to ensure safety of
Singapore's primary food needs, to shoulder the responsibility for
animal and plant health, animal welfare and the agriculture
industry.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of Singapore's primary food requirements come from
overseas while local production supplies only 1.5 percent of the
poultry, 10 percent of fish, 30 percent of the eggs and six
percent of the vegetables consumed in the country.
</P>
<P>
PPD was formed in 1959 to develop and regulate the local
farming industry and to ensure safety and quality of foods
produced by local farms.
</P>
<P>
With the gradual shrinking of the agricultural sector over the
years due to urbanization and industrialization, PPD's role and
focus shifted in tandem to ensure the safety of primary food
imports, manage animal welfare and diseases control and facilitate
agricultural development and trade.
</P>
<P>
As a statutory board, AVA can leveraged on its expertise to
offer consultancy to food and agriculture industries in Singapore
and the region and look into making Singapore an agricultural hub
and distribution center in the region, the minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0090 </DOCNO>
