<HEADLINE> Manila to Firmly Address Internal Security Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada and the country's top officials agreed Friday to firmly
address the internal threats to national security as "they
adversely affect the country's socio-political stability and
economic development."
</P>
<P>
Estrada told the National Security Council Executive Committee
meeting that intermittent incidents of lawlessness, terrorism and
armed insurgency should be dealt with firmly and uncompromisingly.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, attended also by Vice President Gloria-Macapagal
Arroyo, cabinet members and key leaders of Congress, reviewed the
country's security policies and strategies, National Security
Adviser Alexander Aguirre told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre said the meeting discussed the peace process with the
country's rebel groups such as the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (
MILF) and New People's Army (NPA), as well as transnational crime
and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
He said all present agreed to consider the prioritization of
funds intended for the purchase of equipment to address internal
security threats.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the number of the MILF and NPA has increased
to 15,400 and 9,400 respectively at the end of 1999 due to the
Asian financial crisis and the laggard peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to Aguirre, the government will end the internal
armed conflicts through the effective implementation of a package
of policies and programs addressing the socio-economic, political
and military aspects of the problems.
</P>
<P>
He said the attendants also agreed to address regional security
concerns through broader strategic, political, economic and
security alliances and pursuit of peace initiatives bilaterally,
regionally and internationally.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre stressed that the government will pursue a country-team
approach in dealing with national security issues, in which
government agencies shall speak with one voice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
