<P>
ATHENS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Neil Walker, who set two world
records on Thursday, keeps his unbeatable momentum as the American
led qualifiers in the men's 100 meters individual medley on the
second day of the world short-course swimming championships here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Walker took the lead for Friday evening's semi-finals with a
time of 54.57 seconds, beating the challenge from Finn Jani
Sievinen, gold medalist in Thursday's 400m individual medley, who
touched in 54.93.
</P>
<P>
Walker had a flying start on the opening day of the
championships by lowering the 50m backstroke short-course world
mark in the heats and semi-finals on his way to the gold. He also
collected a silver in the medley relay.
</P>
<P>
Compatriot Jenny Thompson, triple gold medalist here last year,
stormed into Friday's 50m butterfly semi-finals with a heat time
of 26.90. Swedish world record holder Anna-Karin Kammerling
qualified a comfortable fourth overall in 27.09.
</P>
<P>
Thompson, who posted the second-fastest women's 100m freestyle
time of 52.92 in Thursday's semi-finals, will face a duel against
Swedish world record holder Therese Alshammar in Friday evening's
100m freestyle final.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia's Martina Moravcova, who won the 1999 Hong Kong world
short-course championships final after Thompson's withdrawal, led
women's 100m individual medley semifinal qualifiers in one minute
2.66 seconds on Friday.
</P>
<P>
South African Brendon Dedekind, who finished runner-up Thursday
in men's 50m breaststroke, led the 50m freestyle qualifiers in 21.
75, ahead of defending champion and world record holder Mark
Foster of Britain, who clocked a smooth 21.77.
</P>
<P>
Briton Paul Palmer, the European long-course champion, led the
qualifiers in men's 400m freestyle with a time of 3:44.67,
followed by Thursday's 200m freestyle bronze medalist Chad Carvin
of the U.S. (3:45.09) and 1997 world short-course champion Jacob
Carstensen of Denmark (3:45.68).
</P>
<P>
Russia's Roman Sludnov, the European short-course champion, led
semi-final qualifiers in the men's 100m breaststroke, while
Australia's Rebecca Brown, former long-course world record holder
now on a comeback, topped the eight final qualifiers in the women'
s 200m breaststroke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
