<HEADLINE> Norwegians Sweep Men's Cross-country Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Erling Jevne of Norway won Friday's
10-kilometer World Cup cross-country classic at Santa Caterina,
Italy as the Norwegian team swept the podium.
</P>
<P>
Johan Muehlegg, who has collected the overall cup to give Spain
its first ever World Cup cross country title, took it easy and
finished just 12th behind the winner.
</P>
<P>
Jevne, a silver medalist for the 50-km event at the 1997 world
championships and 1998 Olympics for the 30km, crossed the finish
line in 25 minutes 54.5 seconds, ahead of teammates Odd-Bjorn
Hjelmeset who clocked at 26:07.0 and Frode Estil in 26:09.01.
</P>
<P>
The German-born Muehlegg, who competes in Spanish colors this
season, has amassed 868 World Cup points with one race remaining.
</P>
<P>
Muehlegg will be shooting for his fifth season victory in
Saturday's 15-K pursuit. 
</P>
