<HEADLINE> Chinese Senior Judges to Receive Training in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Each year, at least six senior
judges and six senior prosecutors will spend three months in
Europe for professional training beginning this year, according to
a four-year cooperative project launched here today.
</P>
<P>
The EU-China Legal and Judicial Co-operation Program, supported
by the European Commission and China's Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation(MOFTEC), also promises to fund 15 Chinese
lawyers each year for their nine-month training courses in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The European Union plans to provide over 13.5 million euro for
the project, which is scheduled to be carried out by by the
British Council (on behalf of the European Commission) and China's
Ministry of Justice (on behalf of MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
According to Gao Changli, Chinese minister of Justice, the
project aims to "strengthen Sino-European legal and judicial
exchanges and collaboration, as well as promoting and ensuring the
overall sound development of China-Europe relations."
</P>
<P>
The project also pledges to fund 20 Chinese professionals each
year on a one-month visit to European legal institutions and to
attend a seminar on a legal topic.
</P>
<P>
Gao pointed out that the Chinese government is devoted to the
rule of law in China, and to building a socialist and legal
country. "The project provides a very good channel for mutual
understanding, learning and co-operation between Chinese and
European legal and judicial circles." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Ax Tools Indicate Similar Intelligence in Asia and Africa (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and American
anthropologists have ascertained that stone artifacts found in
south China were made 800,000 years ago, demonstrating that early
humans living in Asia had a technological level similar to that of
people living in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The stone tools from the Bose Basin in the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region represent the oldest known large cutting tools (
LCTs) in East Asia, pushing the history of toolmaking here back
some 300,000 years.
</P>
<P>
The authoritative Science magazine had a color picture of two
Bose artifacts on the cover of its March 3 issue.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory analysis of argon isotopes, which are widely
regarded as a state-of-the-art dating technique, in the rocks from
Bose precisely dated the aerolites associated with the artifacts.
</P>
<P>
"Acheulean-like tools in the mid-Pleistoncene in south China
imply that Mode 2 technical advances were manifested in East Asia
contemporaneously with handaxe technology in Africa and western
Eurasia," researcher Hou Yamei, professor at the Chinese Academy
of Sciences' Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and
Paleoanthropology, said in the Science report.
</P>
<P>
Because some of the Bose basin artifacts rival the refinement
of contemporaneous African stone tools, known as Acheulean
technology, many scientists claimed that the new study disproves a
long-standing hypothesis that Homo Erectus in Asia was less handy -
- and by implication, less intelligent and adaptive -- than their
African relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Ax Tools Indicate Similar Intelligence in Asia and Africa (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"There is no essential difference in the biology and culture of
early human groups East and West," said co-leader of the
excavation Huang Weiwen, a paleontologist at the same CAS
institute.
</P>
<P>
In 1944, Harvard anthropologist Hallam Movius proposed that
prehistoric population living 1.6 million to 200,000 years ago
existed on one side of a geographical line that separated them
from groups in central and eastern Asia, where early humans
fashioned much simpler stone implements.
</P>
<P>
But the discovery of prehistoric hand axes in the Bose Basin
supports the growing suspicion that hand-ax production sometimes
crossed what archaeologists call the Movius line.
</P>
<P>
With a size of roughly 800 square kilometers, the Bose Basin
has a complete chronological series of layers dated back to two
million years ago, and Hou and her colleagues have found more than
100 ancient cultural sites in the basin.
</P>
<P>
"The stone tools made from large cobbles reveal that ancient
residents there were high-tech Homo Erectus," Hou said.
</P>
<P>
Hou and the team also claim that Bose stone technology is
associated with a meteorite falling to Earth and dispersing glassy
remnants of molten rock.
</P>
<P>
Widespread forest destruction caused by the ancient meteorite
probably spurred residents to make delicate tools in order to
obtain food, they said.
</P>
<P>
"What we have in the Bose Basin is the most Acheulean-like
assemblage of stone tools ever found in East Asia, requiring the
same behavioral and technical competence," said Richard Potts of
the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of Natural History,
who has worked with Hou since 1994.
</P>
<P>
While academic circles take a second look at the Chinese sites,
Hou is leading a team to analyze fossilized animal bones found in
caves surrounding the basin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation in Indonesia's Aceh Improves, Says President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid said here Friday that the situation in Aceh province is much
better now, following talks between State Secretary Bondan Gunawan
and Military Commander of the Aceh Separatist Movement (GAM)
Abdullah Syafi'ie.
</P>
<P>
Wahid added that he had ordered the state secretary to do so.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Gunawan held talks with Syafi'ie in Aceh at an
undisclosed place. This was the first encounter ever between
representatives of the government and the GAM, an underground
movement in the province which has been launching fighting against
the central government over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"I asked Mas (Brother) Bondan to go to Abdullah Syafi'ie and
give sacrificial animals to him," Wahid told reporters after
Friday's praying, adding that the GAM members are also the
brothers of the nation.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Aceh issue should be settled well. He wanted a
large-scale investment process to take place in the province soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesia's House of Representatives (DPR)
Speaker Akbar Tandjung Friday said the government's move to hold
talks with the Aceh separatist commander was expected to
accelerate the peace settlement process on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"The GAM is a fact that exists in Aceh and (its existence) is
effective in some part of the province," Tandjung said, adding
that the government also is expected to extend its talks with
other factions in Aceh to boost the reconciliation process and end
the bloody conflict.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, National Police Chief Gen. Rusdihardjo said
the talks with the GAM commander did not mean that the government
reached a compromise with separatists.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think so. It has been planned long before. It is just
an approach. Let us see from the positive point of view. Talks
with the GAM are better than not at all," Rusdihardjo told
reporters here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Acehnese Muslim leaders voiced their hope that talks
between the government and the GAM will lead to the settlement of
the conflict in the restive province of Aceh.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the cordial meeting between Bondan (Gunawan) and
Syafi'ie to be followed by a get-together between troops of both
sides, thus negating any more gunfight," Chairman of Muhammadiyah
Aceh Chapter Tengku Imam Suja' was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
