<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Company Finds New Partners for Steel Factory in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States corporation
Enron has announced that it has found five partners to work with
it on a proposed factory to manufacture steel slabs in Maputo,
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Maputo Iron and Steel Project (MISP) seemed in deep trouble
last year when Enron's original partner, the South African
Industrial Development Corporation (IDC) pulled out.
</P>
<P>
Enron and IDC were each to have held 50 percent of the equity
in MISP.
</P>
<P>
An Enron press release issued on Thursday says that the other
50 percent will now be held by the Swiss steel company Duferco,
Kobe Steel of Japan, Midrex of the United States, VAI of Australia
and Techint of Italy.
</P>
<P>
Enron says that Midrex has technology for smelting iron filings
that will be used at MISP, while VAI is "one of the major
suppliers and manufacturers of integrated steel equipment in the
world". Techint is also a leading manufacturer of steel-making
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The raw material for MISP is magnetite from Phalaborwa in South
Africa, and natural gas from Pande, in the southern Mozambican
province of Inhambane. Enron holds the rights over the Pande gas
field.
</P>
<P>
According to Enron, MISP will cost about a billion U.S. dollars
to build, with the 610 kilometer-long pipeline to bring the gas
from Pande to Maputo costing a further 500 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But serious problems with MISP have yet to be solved. In
particular, the factory will need 67 million liters of water a
day, and it is not yet known where this will come from. The
government has ruled out the use of the Umbeluzi River, which
supplies Maputo with its drinking water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
