<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Water Forum Opens In Hague </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Over 3,500 experts are
gathering here to take part in the Second World Water Forum in a
bid to create wider public awareness for water issues in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Dutch Crown Prince Willem-Alexander
Claus George Ferdinand said the world needs a new beginning if the
governments are to avert water crises in the century ahead.
</P>
<P>
"This does not mean we will be starting all over again. Instead,
let us take the positive elements from the past and incorporate
them into our new approach to Integrated Water Resource Management,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to the new generation of water managers to work hand
in hand with members of the older generations. By working together,
we will make a difference," added the prince, who is honored as
Chairman of the Forum.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the water situation, Willem-Alexander said lots of
people in the world have no access to clean water or adequate
sanitation.
</P>
<P>
"Millions of people - many of them children - die each year of
water-related diseases: diseases that could easily be cured. Water
resources are in danger of drying up - water that is needed to
produce food and give people sustainable livelihoods. Half of our
wetlands were destroyed in the last century. Half of the world's
rivers are polluted, their ecosystems dead before they reach the
sea," he warned, adding that "this is simply not acceptable".
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the governments hold dialogues with the major
groups attending this Forum and urge them to make a commitment.
</P>
<P>
According to the Organizing Committee, 158 delegations and 115
ministers will attend a parallel Ministerial Conference on water
issues on March 21-22, the last two days of the Forum.
</P>
<P>
World Water Council President Mahmoed Abu-Zeid said the five-
day Forum will be dynamic and creative, expected to provide an
opportunity for all stakeholders to present their concerns and
learn about the needs of others as well.
</P>
<P>
Serving as a launching pad for a global "vision on water", the
Forum aims at paving the way for taking necessary steps "from
Vision to Action".
</P>
<P>
The first World Water Forum was held in Marrakech, Morocco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
