<HEADLINE> Palestinian Court Postpones Hearing of Two Hamas Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Security Court decided on
Friday morning to postpone the hearing session of two suspects of a
radical Palestinian group, who surrendered to the Palestinian
police in the West Bank on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Voice of Palestine radio said Mohammed al-Semari and Hamdi al-
Mikdad urged the jury to put off the hearing session which opened
on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The court met on Thursday night to consider the charges against
the two suspectes of plotting against higher national interests,
illegal possession of arms and explosives in an inhabited area and
risking the lives of the people around.
</P>
<P>
Al-Semari, a leading member of the resistance movement Hamas,
and al-Mikdad were arrested during an ambush by Palestinian
Preventive Security Forces (PSP) at their residence in the West
Bank city of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Security Sources said the accused had threatened to
blow themselves up if the PSP troops broke into their house, but
gave up later after negotiations with the West Bank PSP Chief,
Colonel Gabriel al-Ragoub and Ghassan al-Shuk'a, the head of Nablus
Municipality.
</P>
<P>
They surrendered to the police after making a telephone
conversation with Hamas supreme leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin arranged
by Palestinian officials, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian Security Forces on Thursday afternoon
arrested another Palestinian suspected to be in connection with the
two defendants as tipped by the Israeli Public Security Police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
