<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Reaches Agreement With Major Suppliers of Oral Polio Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) has reached an agreement with the three largest
international suppliers of oral polio vaccine (OPV) to ensure that
sufficient quantities of the vaccine are available at least
through the year 2005, when the world is expected to be certified
polio-free.
</P>
<P>
"The global campaign to eradicate polio will not succeed if the
supply of oral polio vaccine is not assured through the year 2005
and even beyond," said UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy in
a statement here Friday. "The agreements we have come to today are
a major stepping stone toward our goal of eradicating this disease.
"
</P>
<P>
Meeting in Geneva with senior representatives of the three
principal WHO-certified suppliers of oral polio vaccine, Aventis
Pasteur, Chiron and SmithKline Beecham Biologicals, Bellamy said
that the business of vaccine production goes far beyond profit and
loss.
</P>
<P>
"It has a humanitarian dimension," Bellamy said. "It's
important to remind ourselves that this vaccine is one of the
miracles of our times."
</P>
<P>
As the target date for eradicating polio gets closer, UNICEF is
going all-out to support eradication efforts in countries where
the disease is still endemic. In collaboration with WHO, Rotary
International, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and
NGOs, "National Immunization Days" will reach over 450 million
children with the oral polio vaccine this year alone.
</P>
<P>
Eradication of polio is targeted for the end of this year;
final certification that polio has truly been swept from every
corner of the globe is targeted for 2005.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF spends about 100 million U.S. dollars each year to
provide oral polio vaccine for immunization programs in polio-
endemic countries, mainly in sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
