<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Regain 4.43 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index rose for the first time this week
up 329.04 points, or 2.01 percent, to open at 16,688.04 on Friday
morning after a decline of four consecutive trading days since
Monday. Affected by the regional markets, Hong Kong stocks fell
all the way down about 1,500 points in the week.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks took their cue from the Dow Jones Industrial
Average's record point gain on Thursday after positive inflation
news eased concerns that the Federal Reserve will raise rates
substantially this week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that there were signs that U.S. inflation is not
up as strongly as previously thought and Internet rates may not be
that much of a worry.
</P>
<P>
The Friday's turnover was 12.363 billion HK dollars (1.585
billion U.S. dollars), 612 million HK dollars (78 million U.S.
dollars) less than Thursday's 12.975 billion HK dollars (1.663
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the four sub-indices of the Hang Seng Index, Finance,
Utilities, Properties and Commerce and Industry rose 4.69 percent,
1.08 percent, 4.06 percent and 4.68 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index also gained 2.88 percent
as the Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporation Index was up 3.22
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
