<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eximbank Supports Export of Oil Tankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The China Export and Import Bank
(Eximbank) announced today that it will provide 370 million U.S.
dollars in export sellers' credit and export credit insurance to
support the export of five giant oil tankers to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Eximbank signed a contract here today with the China
Shipbuilding Industry Corporation (CSIC) and the China
Shipbuilding Company Ltd. (CSTC) on the financing.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the project said that this is the first time
that China has received overseas orders for building extra-large
oil tankers, and is also the largest export credit the Eximbank
has granted sine it was founded six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the Eximbank will provide a credit package
of 1.79 billion yuan and 110 million U.S. dollars for the project,
and underwrite 500 million U.S. dollars in export credit insurance.
</P>
<P>
The CSIC, China's largest shipbuilding group organized only not
long ago, has 48 manufacturing enterprises, 28 research institutes,
five regional offices and 15 share-holding companies. The company
is capable of building oil tankers ranging from 10,000 tons to 300,
000 tons, as well as other kinds of ships.
</P>
<P>
The CSTC is a large professional trading company specialized in
the export of ships and ship equipment.
</P>
<P>
The Eximbank is a policy bank primarily offering financing
support to the export of machinery and electronic products,
complete set of equipment, new and high technology products and,
particularly, ships. So far the bank has financed 27.27 billion
yuan to support the export of 480 ships, totaling 11.5 million
tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
