<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Prefers not to Send Police to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Israel is inclined to reject an
American appeal about sending Israeli police officials to Kosovo to
participate in the international police force positioned there to
maintain order.
</P>
<P>
Although Israel has not yet given an official reply to the
United States, the heads of Israeli police and officials in the
Public Security Ministry had expressed their opposition to such an
idea, the Ha'aretz daily Friday quoted officials familiar with the
plan as saying.
</P>
<P>
These officials contended that according to the Israeli law, the
police have no legal ground to exercise its authority outside the
borders of the country.
</P>
<P>
The request, according to the report, was made by U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright to Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
after an initial request from a lower-level U.S. official was
rejected outright earlier.
</P>
<P>
Levy reportedly favored accepting the appeal, but internal
consultations later turned the responsibility of making a decision
to the Public Security Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official told the Ha'aretz that the incident will not
pose any obstacle or problem to relations between Israel and the U.
S., the major patron of Israel in the world political arena.
</P>
<P>
Israel once acceded to a similar U.S. request to send police
force to Haiti after the U.S. invasion of the Caribbean island
country several years ago. U.S. President Bill Clinton then
intervened in a direct appeal to the then Israeli Prime Minister
Yithzak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
However, the complicated situation in Kosovo made Israelis hold
back from following the precedence. The escalating ethnic violence
in Kosovo, especially in the northern city of Kosovoska-Mitrovica,
caused more than 100 injuries this year on the part of
international peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
According to Yugoslav official statistics, so far about 910
civilians have been killed and more than 800 injured in 4,354
terrorist activities since the international peacekeepers entered
Kosovo in June last year after the 78-day air bombing of Yugoslavia
by the U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0144 </DOCNO>
