<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- Marc Grossman, the United States assistant secretary of state
for affairs with Europe, said Thursday that significant progress
had been recorded in the fields of democracy and human rights in
Turkey since June, 1999 when the 57th government led by Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit came to power.
</P>
<P>
Grossman noted that the Turkish government was on the right
direction in regard to carrying out reforms, adding that Turkey's
efforts would succeed in extending the freedom of thought and
putting an end to torture.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Unidentified assailants staged on Thursday an armed attack on
a police vehicle in Kartal district of Istanbul, the largest city
of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Policeman Mustafa Yazici was injured when the assailants opened
fire on the vehicle which was patrolling around the district, and
he was taken to a nearby hospital for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Security forces launched an operation, and detained two
suspects. A full investigation into the attack is underway.
</P>
<P>
Cumhuriyet (Republic):
</P>
<P>
-- The number of Turkish pilgrims who lost their lives in this
year's hajj in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, increased to 23, including
Nizamettin Sevgili, the Siirt Deputy of Motherland Party (ANAP),
who died of a heart failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
