<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Grow 32.7 percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Thai exports in February reached
5.57 billion U.S. dollars, posing a 32.7 percent year-on-year
increase, Thai Deputy Commerce Minister Gornpot Asavinvichit said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gornpot was quoted by Thailand News Agency as saying that
Thailand also gained a trade surplus of 789.5 million dollars last
month, a 34.3 percent increase over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The figures were satisfactory and if the country could maintain
a monthly export level at around 5.5 billion dollars in the rest
of the year, total exports this year could grow over 10 percent,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured products accounted for the largest proportion of
the country's exports last month, led by electrical appliances,
computers and parts and other electronic products, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited improving world economic conditions, growing capital
markets and rising electronic commerce businesses as the factors
that contributed to the growth.
</P>
<P>
This year, the Thai government will push for more exports of
agricultural products through government-to-government deals,
Gornpot said.
</P>
<P>
Due to growing demand for capital goods of local manufacturers,
Thai imports in February also posed a 31 percent year-on-year
increase, reaching 4.78 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
