<HEADLINE> Swiss Legislators Back Calls for Duty-Free Stock Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss House of Representatives
has given support to calls to scrap stamp duty on the trading of
shares and bonds in order to make the country a more attractive
financial center, Swiss Radio International reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The House voted 107 votes to 58 for the federal government to
come up with a proposal by September to do away with stamp duty on
shares and bonds,
</P>
<P>
If the stamp duty on shares and bonds is scrapped, the
government will suffer a loss of around 500 million Swiss francs (
about 301 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democrats, who are opposed to the plan, claimed that
they will call for a nation-wide vote, unless the banking sector
offers some kind of compensation to make up the shortfall in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
But center-right parties said the measures were needed for
Switzerland's financial market to remain competitive with other
major centers like London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0151 </DOCNO>
