<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak Renews Sponsorship of Olympic Games for Another Eight Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Eastman Kodak Company has
renewed its worldwide Olympic sponsorship for the eight-year
period from 2001 through 2008, announced the International Olympic
Committee (IOC) Thursday in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
"We are delighted that Kodak, who supported the first Olympic
Games of the modern era in Athens in 1896, will again be with us
when we return to Athens in 2004," said Richard W. Pound, IOC
first vice president and chairman of the IOC Marketing Commission.
</P>
<P>
"For more than a hundred years, Kodak has been making the
Olympic experience real for the people of the world. Olympic
images continue to be the most powerful reminders of the grace and
glory of the Olympic athletes," Mr. Pound added. "They say a
picture is worth a thousand words; Kodak has provided the
equivalent of millions of Olympic memories during its more than a
century of support of the Olympic Games."
</P>
<P>
By joining the fifth and sixth generations of the IOC's global
sponsorship program, The Olympic Partnership (TOP) Program, Kodak
remains the exclusive film/photographics and imaging provider
through the next four Olympic Games: the 2002 Olympic Winter Games
in Salt Lake City, the 2004 Olympic Games in Athens, the 2006
Olympic Winter Games in Turin, and the 2008 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
As a TOP partner, Kodak also continues to sponsor the athletic
teams and activities of the 199 National Olympic Committees (NOCs)
around the world.
</P>
<P>
Kodak has been involved in the Olympic Movement since 1896 when
it was an advertiser in the Athens results brochure and is a
charter member of the TOP program. Kodak joins The Coca-Cola
Company (beverages), John Hancock (life insurance/annuities), Sema
Group (information technology/systems integration), TIME/Sports
Illustrated (publishing), and VISA (payment systems) as the latest
partner in TOP V.
</P>
<P>
"We believe our role with the Olympics over the last century
plus has really furthered the goal of supporting the Olympic
spirit, athletic competition and international unity. In addition
to providing products, services, technology and personnel to help
make the games a reality, Kodak's products have also helped
capture some of the most enduring images of the Games. Those
images, in turn, have helped communicate the spirit of the
Olympics around the world," said Carl Gustin, senior vice
president and chief marketing officer, Eastman Kodak Company.
</P>
<P>
The IOC's TOP (The Olympic Partners) Program is the only
worldwide Olympic sponsor program. Created in 1985, the TOP
program provides support to the organizing committees of the
summer and winter Olympic Games, every National Olympic Committee,
the athletes of the Olympic teams, and the IOC.
</P>
<P>
When the program was launched, fewer than ten NOCs had any form
of marketing revenue. Today all 199 NOCs receive funding through
the program, according to the IOC. TOP Partners enjoy exclusivity
in their respective business categories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13-year-old Israeli Girl Draws with Kasparov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A 13-year-old Israeli girl
played world chess champion Garry Kasparov to a draw this week,
the Ha'aretz daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The girl, named Victoria Zaks, participated in a worldwide
match for Children versus Kasparov via the Internet and forced the
champion agree to a peace treaty after only 13 moves, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
All the other children taking part in the match were defeated
by Kasparov in a few moves, so that Zaks was the only one
challenging Kasparov's nerve.
</P>
<P>
Zaks immigrated from a former Soviet Union country to Israel
just two yeas ago and she has been reportedly playing chess since
she was six. She did not make any special preparations for the
match and was not especially nervous, the report said.
</P>
<P>
To encourage her bravery and brightness, Israel's National
Lottery decided to award her a new computer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
