with Lebanon in July will be severe.
</P>
<P>
Barak also reiterated the government's commitment to Israel's
ally, the South Lebanese Army, and said the safety and welfare of
members of the force and their families will be guaranteed,
whatever the cost.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was speaking to reporters while on a tour of
Northern Israel Thursday, during which he participated in a
memorial ceremony marking the 80th anniversary of the death of a
Jewish fighter.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Policy-making officials in Israel say the United States is
not doing enough to curb Russian aid for Iran's nuclear weapons and
long-range missile projects. Although the administration assured
Israel the subject was high on its agenda, the officials say, there
is no connection between the words and actions.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem expects the U.S. to exert heavier pressure on the
leadership in Moscow and to warn the Russians that they will face
sanctions if nuclear and missile technology continues to be made
available to Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, the administration has more complex considerations in
its relations with Russia, notably maintaining the stability of the
regime of acting President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian preventive security units arrested three Hamas
suspects near Nablus on Thursday night, two of them believed to be
the last members of the terror cell liquidated in Taibeh on March
2.
</P>
<P>
The two, reportedly armed with two suitcases containing 10
kilograms of explosive each, were arrested at their hideout.
</P>
<P>
A national security alert had been launched following the raid
on the Taibeh cell, during which four terrorists were killed and a
fifth arrested.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel and U.S. officials sought Thursday night to tone down
expectations of a quick resumption of peace talks with Syria
following predictions by Syrian Defense Minister Mustafa Tlass that
the negotiations could resume in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We are working on it, the time constraints are tightening, but
we still do not know anything new about the resumption of talks,"
said a spokesman from Barak's office.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin said "I am
not aware of any imminent announcement" of negotiations resumption.
At the same time, Rubin did not rule out the possibility of a
summit between Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and U.S. President
Bill Clinton to help jumpstart the process.  
</P>
