<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Education Sector Urged to Nurture More Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi Friday urged the education sector
to step up their efforts in generating an innovation environment
for students to explore their talents.
</P>
<P>
A country's competitive edge would increasingly come from its
ability to research, innovate and develop new technologies and
scientific techniques and the education sector should step up
their efforts in fulfilling this necessity, he told the opening of
the Prime College Campus in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
He said there was an urgent need for Malaysia to increase the
number of scientists and engineers who will form the catalytic
backbone to the country's transition to a competitive knowledge
economy,
</P>
<P>
If Malaysia was to realize its quantum leap into the digital
era, a critical mass of scientists and researchers was a pre-
requisite, he said.
</P>
<P>
And if Malaysia was to succeed in creating a knowledge-based
economy where the best ideas can flourish, then an environment of
innovations must be generated by allowing students to explore
their talents fully, he added.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said the continued development of private institutions
of higher learning must take into account the need to make private
education accessible to students.
</P>
<P>
Under the 7th Malaysia Plan (1996-2000), the target for upper
secondary school enrollment into the science stream was set at 60
percent, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
