<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Nike Inc. Reports 17 Percent Profit Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Nike Inc., U.S.'s leading
athletic shoe vendor, reported Thursday a 17-percent jump in
fiscal third-quarter earnings, amid solid sales growth
internationally and despite falling revenue.
</P>
<P>
News release from the sports giant said that, for the quarter
ended February 29, 2000, the Beaverton, Oregon-based company,
earned net income of 145.3 million U.S. dollars, up from 124.2
million dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Revenue fell to 2.16 billion dollars, down slightly from 2.18
billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to show strong growth in profitability despite
significant pressure caused by the strength of the U.S. dollar
against the euro," said Philip Knight, Nike chairman and chief
executive officer, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Our international business is robust, showing constant dollar
revenue growth in every region outside the U.S.," he added.
</P>
<P>
By region, U.S. athletic footwear revenue rose 4 percent to 858.
9 million dollars, while European revenue fell 7 percent to 558.5
million dollars -- but a rising dollar was responsible for that
decline, Nike said. Revenue in the Asia-Pacific area rose 14
percent to 254.1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Nike earned 453
million dollars, compared to 357 million dollars a year ago.
Revenue during that span rose 2 percent to 6.7 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Northwest Airlines Raises Ticket Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Northwest Airlines
Thursday raised fares throughout its entire domestic system, by as
much as 40 U.S. dollars per round-trip, in an attempt to counter
historically high fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
News release from the No. 4 U.S. airlines said it raised
unrestricted, or business, fares by 20 to 40 dollars round-trip,
and leisure fares by 10 to 20 dollars round-trip. Other fares,
such as senior fares, military fares, some Internet offers and
consolidator fares, vary in their levels of increase.
</P>
<P>
Northwest also increased fees for services such as excess
luggage, pet transportation, lost ticket replacement and other
handling fees by 5-25 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Observers expected other airlines to follow suit. "This will
probably be one of the fastest fare hike matches," said Tom
Parsons, who tracks fares for on-line travel company Bestfares.com.
</P>
<P>
Northwest executives, including chief executive John Dasburg,
have recently said current fuel price levels threaten airline
profitability.
</P>
<P>
Fuel price, rising to more than 30 dollars per barrel, is the
second-largest cost for airlines after labor.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Bethune, chief executive officer of Continental Airlines,
also said recently that fares would have to rise to offset fuel
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo on Wall Street Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose sharply in Tokyo
Friday, helped by Thursday's surge on Wall Street, with the
benchmark Nikkei index closing above 19,500 for the first time in
five trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange soared 313.09 points, or 1.63
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 19,566.32.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, rose 28.65 points, or 1.74 percent, to 1,674.
22.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 739.20 million
shares from Thursday's 653.04 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Trading house Nissho Iwai Corp. was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Investors felt good about buying stocks as several new
investment trusts are expected to be launched by the end of this
month, traders said.
</P>
<P>
An upgraded economic assessment by the Economic Planning Agency
(EPA) has also improved market sentiment in Tokyo, they said.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were higher in 30 of the 33 business sectors.
</P>
<P>
The electrical machinery sector rose 1.46 percent, reflecting
Thursday's performance on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones
Industrial Average jumped 499.19 points, a record one-day point
gain, to 10,630.60.
</P>
<P>
Sectors of information and telecom, transportation machinery,
real estate and rubber industry drew active buying.
</P>
<P>
Losers included the fishery, agriculture and forestry sector,
the air transportation sector and the nonlife insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers far exceeded
losers 803 to 433, with 174 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
