<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Carry Out Regional Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) is to carry out a regional comparative
study to determine the economic environment differences in all its
member states as implementation of the Free Trade Area (FTA) draws
nearer, secretary-general Erastus Mwencha has disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The study would examine the various factors to determine
differences from country to country which would in turn offer
solutions to uneven playing field, he said.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Zambian newspaper, The Post, quoted Mwencha as saying
that at the moment people were apprehensive for the outcome of
the regional grouping's zero tariffs scheduled for October 31,
2000.
</P>
<P>
"We have to tackle the economic environment problem and examine
the existing inconsistencies. I believe that is the real challenge
of integration," Mwencha said.
</P>
<P>
He cited concerns from the Zambian private sector which has
highlighted high government taxes, interest rates, labor and
electricity costs as contributing to its disadvantaged position
and uneven playing field.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha reiterated that COMESA has instituted a mechanism to
compensate revenue loss that may be incurred by national
governments as a result of zero rating.
</P>
<P>
He said the compensation mechanism was put up with the
co-operation of some major donors including the European Union and
International Development Bank. 
</P>
