<HEADLINE> Mozambique needs 50 Years to Rebuild Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican High Commissioner
(ambassador) to Zambia Christafo Jamo has said that his country
will need more than 50 years to rebuild the infrastructure
destroyed by the floods.
</P>
<P>
While receiving some relief donations, Jamo said almost a third
of his country has been devastated to an extent where there are no
roads, bridges, schools and health centers, Zambia Daily Mail
newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jamo also revealed that the Paris Club of western creditor
nations had suspended Mozambique's 73 million U.S. dollars debt
service payment to help the country recover from the worst flood
in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
He said however the international community would have
preferred the debt to be cancelled.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has an external debt of 8.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
