<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Chinese Cities Report Improved Air This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The quality of air in most major
Chinese cities improved slightly this week as wide-ranging
rainfall helped clean the air, the China Environmental Monitoring
Center said today in a weekly Air Quality Report.
</P>
<P>
From March 10 to 16, Beijing, Hohhot, Shijiazhuang, Xi'an,
Chongqing, Tianjin and seven other cities reported slight air
pollution, while Urumqi and Taiyuan reported poor air.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen cities in southeastern and southern China, including
Shenzhen, Shanghai, Fuzhou, Suzhou, Haikou, Zhanjiang, and Xiamen
enjoyed excellent air.
</P>
<P>
Jinan, Nanchang, Wuhan, Guangzhou, Harbin, Shenyang, and 12
other cities reported good air.
</P>
<P>
Urumqi, Taiyuan, Shijiazhuang and 27 other cities listed
suspended particles as the major pollutant. Sulfur dioxide was the
major pollutant in Changsha, Chongqing and Guiyang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
