<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friendly Exposes Soccer Gap between China and Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By sportswriter Liu Guang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Sense comes after sentiment.
</P>
<P>
After reading too much into the friendly between China and
Japan Wednesday in Kobe, the Chinese media has shifted the focus
from head coach Yugoslav Bora Milutinovic to where China stand in
the hierarchy of Asia soccer, let alone the world.
</P>
<P>
Milutinovic, nicknamed "Wonder Coach" for guiding four
different teams into the World Cup finals, had hit the headlines
in sports pages in the build-up to the friendly which ended up a
scoreless tie.
</P>
<P>
The habitually hectic media spared the Yugoslav from scolding
but laid their fingers to the sore spot of the Chinese soccer,
which they held has lagged behind Japan whether in soccer
philosophy or tactics.
</P>
<P>
"The goalless draw could not whitewash the alarming soccer gap
between China and Japan. But Milutinovic took over the national
team just a week ago, he need not shoulder any reponsibility,"
said the mass-circulation weekly Ball Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Daily even gave thumbs-up to Milutinovic for his
substitution in the second half, thinking the replacement was well-
timed and effective.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise the result would not have been a draw,"said the
daily paper.
</P>
<P>
Instead of Milutinovic, the media has relentlessly directed
their sharp words towards the beleaguered Chinese soccer, which
was embodied by poor organisation and shabby teamwork on the field.
</P>
<P>
"Visible Gap" was the headline of the Beijing Morning Post on
Thursday, which warned that the Japanese soccer has had an all-
round advantage over China.
</P>
<P>
The paper summed up the gap as "skillfully and tactically
stagnant and weak mentally, the single physical advantage failed
to be brought into full play".
</P>
<P>
China Sports Daily said that among the Chinese players the
goalkeeper is the best while the China Youth Daily headlined "
China forced a lucky tie".
</P>
<P>
"What the Chinese players are in urgent need are the basics:
skill and ability to read the game," said the paper.
</P>
<P>
China did not have a mental disadvantage as both sides split
their past meet with a 7-2-7 record. The last time they met on the
field is in 1998 in Dynasty Cup soccer tournament where China won
2-0.
</P>
<P>
The unbridled buildup prior to the friendly belied China's gap
to Japan, which football legend Pele ever said have the "talent,
quality and the finess with the ball like Brazilians" and "the
power of European style".
</P>
<P>
Japan's J-league, home to dozens of Brazilian players, has
slowly grown into a bit of an exporting industry seven years after
its birth. Midfielders Hidetoshi Nakata (AS Roma) and Hiroshi
Nanami (Venezia) and striker Shoji Jo (Real Valladolid)
spearheaded the up-and-coming generation to put Japanese soccer on
the world map.
</P>
<P>
The Sports Express went further to say that the gap is the
price that the Chinese soccer paid for the "detour" they made.
</P>
<P>
"Japanese soccer has unswervingly hold on to the South American
playing style, now they begin to harvest the crops.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, the Chinese soccer fall short of its own
style. They imitated Brazil then England, recently they turned to
the so-called Euro-Latin style. It is really a lesson that so much
time have been spent on the detour but come to no avail,"
</P>
<P>
"If we do not draw the lessons, China will lose matches which
matter much more than the friendly," the paper warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
