<HEADLINE> Anhui Steps Up Wetland Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province has set
up three state-level wetland reserves covering more than 200,000
ha. in total, providing havens for many endangered wildlife
species.
</P>
<P>
The areas under protection include one nature habitat
especially for the Yangtze crocodiles in Xuanzhou, and two others
for water birds in Chizhou and Anqing.
</P>
<P>
The province has also made increasing efforts to protect an
additional 3.9 million ha. of local wetland, which accounts for 28
percent of the provincial land area.
</P>
<P>
Wetland preservation has been playing an important role in
Anhui's water storage, climate readjustment, and flood and
pollution control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
