<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Signs of Self-sustaining Recovery Seen in Japan's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy has shown the first
signs of a self-sustaining recovery since the latest recession
from April 1997, the Economic Planning Agency said Friday in its
monthly report for March.
</P>
<P>
The economy still "continues to improve moderately", but signs
of a self-sustaining recovery have "gradually appeared", said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The recovery was ascribed to a pickup in capital investment,
improvement of corporate returns and removal of inventory burdens,
according to agency officials.
</P>
<P>
It is corporate activities that upgraded the March assessment
and the personal consumption also did some contribution as low
bonuses weighed on household spending, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki said the government
is not yet ready to declare that Japan's economy is on a
sustainable recovery path since "The recovery in domestic demand
is still weak." 
</P>
</TEXT>
