<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alert Level Over Mt. Mayon Lowered Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine volcanologists have
lowered to Alert Level 3 the disaster warning over Mt. Mayon after
it exhibited a continuous decline in eruptive parameters since
last week,Philippine News Agency (PNA) said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement, however, was twice greeted by 1 kilometers
high of billowing ash columns emerging from the crater, the
Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs) was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But volcanologists were fast to confirm it was not eruption-
related, the PNA said, adding that it was brought about by a
sectoral collapse of pyroclastic deposits from the crater that
triggered a mushrooming effect of thick ashes.
</P>
<P>
On March 9, the Phivolcs lowered Mt. Mayon's warning status to
Alert Level Four, after the volcano had a sudden drop in all
parameters of abnormal condition.
</P>
<P>
As this developed, evacuees have been reduced to 27,602 or an
equivalent to 5,596 families, the Albay Provincial Disaster
Management Office said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 80,000 people fled foothill villages after the volcano
began its latest series of eruptions on February 24. There have
been no reported casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
