<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Hydropower Station Put Into Service in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- One more hydropower station in
Myanmar's northeastern Shan state was commissioned into service
Thursday, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Zawgyi hydropower station in Yaksauk township is the 14th
built in the Shan state.
</P>
<P>
With two 6-megawatt turbines, the power station was built at a
cost of 10.1 million U.S. dollars plus 51.41 million Kyats (160,
000 dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
Installed with machinery and facilities brought from China
under contracts with China's Yunnan Machinery and Equipment Import
and Export Corporation, and China Shanghai Corporation for Foreign
Economic and Technological Cooperation, the power project was
completed in October 1998 and test run began then.
</P>
<P>
The Zawgyi hydropower station, with its dam, also has the
capacity of supplying water for cultivation of crops all year
round,affecting 4,455 hectares, the report added.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the installed capacity of
state-run Myanma Electric Power Enterprise was 1,058 megawatts at
the end of October 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
