<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Diplomacy to Focus on European Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
VIENNA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Austria's diplomatic policies will
focus on promoting and deepening European Union expansion in the
years to come, Austrian Foreign Minister Benita Ferrero-Waldner
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Telling reporters at a press conference, she said she would
conduct responsibly the rotating presidency of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), advancing and
deepening the process of EU enlargement, and quickly handle all
compensation issues generated from World War II.
</P>
<P>
Austria agreed on Wednesday to compensate those Ukrainians who
were forced to work in Austria during World War II.
</P>
<P>
According to a committee's investigation report, about 40,000
out of 240,000 forced laborers still alive are Ukrainians.
</P>
<P>
But prompting and deepening the process of the 15-nation
European group is the top agenda of her work, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ferrero-Waldner noted that the expansion of the bloc is not
only an economic program, but also a program of peace, security
and culture.
</P>
<P>
Austria, located in the heart of Europe, has every reason to
help its east and south neighbors to join the union, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she pointed out that speed and quality are two
important factors in expanding the EU, saying it is necessary to
maintain a certain speed to quicken the access of candidate
nations.
</P>
<P>
But quality should not be neglected, she said,because the
guarantee of expansion quality is the precondition for balancing
the benefits of current and future members of the group.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the far-right Freedom Party's attitude toward the
EU's enlargement, Ferrero-Waldner replied that as a partner of the
two-party coalition government, it will act under the coalition's
plan.
</P>
<P>
Austria has been diplomatically isolated by other European
countries for allowing the Freedom Party, headed by Jorg Haider
who is notorious for remarks belittling Nazi employment policies,
to enter the government last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
