<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's GDP Expected to Grow by 0.2 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's central bank
predicted in its annual report that the country's gross domestic
product (GDP) is expected to grow by 0.2 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The central Bank, Bank Indonesia, said production activities
had already started to recover.
</P>
<P>
It cited in particular the processing industries, services,
electricity, gas and drinking water and agricultural sectors.
</P>
<P>
It admitted, however, that the economic recovery process was
still sensitive to any socio-political upheavals.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a memorandum of economic and financial policies
signed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the government
issued in January this year, Indonesia's economy is predicted to
grow by 1-2 percent in 1999/2000 fiscal year ending on March 31,
2000 and then strengthening to the 3-4 percent during the fiscal
year 2000(April-December).
</P>
<P>
The central bank stated that the country's foreign debt dropped
by 6.3 percent this year to 141.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Private debt decreased by 21.5 percent while state debt
increased by 12.5 percent, the central bank said in its annual
report published by the Antara News Agency here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although total foreign debt had decreased, the report said, the
burden of repaying the principals and interest remained heavy and
hampered the recovery of export activities.
</P>
<P>
It further said foreign debt settlement had been relatively
slow except in the case of banks' and government's debts.
</P>
<P>
Only up to 14.7 percent of 23.2 billion U.S. dollars in non-
banks' private debts had been restructured.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, restructuring of government debts had been
quite successful reaching 79.8 percent of 4.7 billion U.S. dollars
expected to be restructured this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Rejects U.S. Report on Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a press release available here Friday, the Myanmar Foreign
Ministry said that Myanmar regrets over the report on its labor
conditions which in no way represents the true situation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. report charges that Myanmar uses forced labor with
impunity to support tourism and for commercial ventures of the
military.
</P>
<P>
The press release also refuted U.S. accusation of use of forced
labor by Myanmar in military operations, saying that no major
military operations have taken place in recent years since 17 anti-
government armed groups have returned to the legal fold and peace
and stability prevail all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The press release turned down the allegation that children are
used in Myanmar as human minesweepers and shields, saying that
there is no need to dignify them with a response.
</P>
<P>
The press release blamed the U.S. report of ignoring the
positive actions taken by the Myanmar government in its
legislation regarding labor, citing the order of the country's
Ministry of Home Affairs issued on May 14, 1999 forbidding the use
of forced labor.
</P>
<P>
The press release charged that the U.S. report, which has
nothing to do with labor, is politically motivated, timed to
coincide with the meetings of the International Labor Organization
Governing Body and Human Rights Commission in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar announced dissociation of itself in June
1999 from a resolution adopted at the 87th session of the
International Labor Conference which accused the country of
widespread use of forced labor and restriction of freedom of
association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
