<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Approves Mexico's Anti-Drug Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Commission
on Drugs has approved a resolution on drug consumption by children,
a program presented by the Mexican government, the Foreign
Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a communique that the U.N. body approved
the program at its 43rd session being held in Vienna, Austria,
under the title "International Cooperation to Prevent Drug
Consumption by Children."
</P>
<P>
The resolution calls on U.N. member states to implement
prevention programs, training plans and other measures with the
participation of the community to deal with the problem of the
consumption and abuse of illicit drugs by minors.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. body acknowledges the international character of the
problem and promotes international cooperation in the prevention
of drug consumption, as well as medical treatment for minors.
</P>
<P>
It also calls on the states to give priority to the Plan of
Action for the application of the Declaration of the Rector
Principles of the Drugs Demand approved last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
