<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Armed Group's Former Leader Assassinated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The former leader of the Andres
Castro United Front (FUAC) armed group Edmundo Olivias, also known
as "Camilo Turcios," was shot dead Thursday by unidentified gunmen
in a road in the northeast of Nicaragua, said police sources.
</P>
<P>
Olivias and his driver Francisco Contreras were slain when they
were traveling early Thursday morning in a pickup truck on the
road to the city of Boaco, 90 kilometers northeast of Managua.
</P>
<P>
Olivias' wife Doriel Caceres, who was traveling in the same
vehicle, was seriously wounded after being struck by seven shots.
She was taken to a Managua hospital, said Boaco police chief
Commissioner Alfonso Sevilla.
</P>
<P>
The FUAC is an armed group made up mainly by members of the
defunct Sandinista Popular Army. They struck a demobilization
agreement in December 1997 with the government of President
Arnoldo Aleman.
</P>
<P>
Still, some group members refused to surrender their weapons
and continue to take action. The FUAC kidnapped a Canadian
engineer and a Nicaraguan soldier in a sector of the North
Atlantic Autonomous Region of the country last September.
</P>
<P>
"Turcios" was an intermediary in the negotiations between the
government and the kidnappers, leading to release of the two
hostages in October.
</P>
<P>
The FUAC second chief, Jorge Alejandro Navarro, also known as "
Tito Fuentess," was also assassinated in the mining village of
Rosita by unknown gunmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
