<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Supports Venezuelan Oil Prices Range </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There is fluctuation in markets, but all of them need
stabilization mechanisms, the Director of the Energy Council Lori
Cameron said in an interview with the El Universal newspaper
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cameron proposed that the fluctuation range should neither be
too high for consumers, nor too low for producers.
</P>
<P>
Cameron is now in Venezuela accompanied by U.S. Alaska state
government representative Joe Green, and Sandra Bailey, president
of the Legislative Research on Energy and Environment Center.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices touched bottom in 1998 and began to soar in early
April 1999 after an agreement on cutting the international supply
of crude was signed. Oil prices reached their highest point of
more than 30 U.S. dollars per barrel this year.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, Venezuela, Saudi Arabia and other oil-producing
countries support an increase in the oil supply to reduce prices
to protect the world economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
