<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Satisfied with Ties with Bolivia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso expressed satisfaction Thursday with the sound
bilateral relations between his country and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso made the statement after meeting with visiting Bolivian
President Hubo Banzer, who was here on a three-day state visit
that started Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian president said that good bilateral relations are
based on the harmonious coexistence, frankness in dialogs,
coordination of positions in international issues as a whole, as
well as the cooperative standpoint on common regional challenges.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso reaffirmed that his country supports the full admission
of Bolivia to the Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Currently, Bolivia and Chile are associate members of the
Mercosur, which is composed of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Banzer briefed Cardoso on the political and economic conditions
of his country, reaffirming the strategic priority it has kept on
the continuous development of the Bolivia-Brazil relations.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Brazil's state oil company Petroleos
Brazilenos and Bolivia's oil field signed an accord under which
Brazil will import 30 million cubic meters of natural gas per day
from Bolivia till the year 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
