<HEADLINE> Johnson Hints at Final Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- American athlete Michael
Johnson, the double world record holder in the 200 and 400 meters,
on Thursday arrived in South Africa for the Engen Grand Prix
series with the news that this Olympic year may be his last in
athletic competition.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who is going for a repeat of his double Olympic gold
medals in Sydney in September, will compete in the 200 meters in
Pietersburg on Saturday against South Africa's Marcus la Grange
and Morne Nagel.
</P>
<P>
He will again contest the 200 meters in Pretoria on March 24,
with a grande finale in the 400 meters in Cape Town on March 31.
</P>
<P>
"This will probably be my last Olympics," said the 32-year-old
sprint ace. "And if I compete next year, it will certainly be my
last season."
</P>
<P>
Johnson said he was pleased to be back in South Africa because
he always had a good year when he started off his season in the
Rainbow Nation.
</P>
<P>
Last year he got going on a similar program in the Engen series
and went on to break the 400m record at the World Championships in
Seville. 
</P>
</TEXT>
