<HEADLINE> Court Overturns Positive Test for Swimmer: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand swimmer Trent Bray
will take part in the selection competitions later this month for
the Sydney Olympics after a judge overturned his positive doping
test result, the New Zealand Herald reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The court ruling was based on doubts about containers used in
one part of the test and the length of time between a sample being
taken from Bray in November and the test undertaken after
Christmas, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The sample sat in quarantine for two weeks on its way to a
testing laboratory in Sydney, according to Bray's lawyer Peter
Thorp.
</P>
<P>
Bray was a triple short-course world championship silver
medallist. He also took a Commonwealth Games freestyle silver
medal in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
