<HEADLINE> More World Records Broken on First Day of Short-course Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Four world records and three
championships records were set Thursday, the opening day of the
5th World Short-course Swimming Championships in the indoor pool
of the Athens Olympic Sports complex.
</P>
<P>
The world records were set by Neil Walker from the United
States in the 50-meter backstroke with 23.42, Lars Frolander from
Sweden in the 100-meter butterfly with 50.59, the Swedish men's
team in the 4x100 freestyle with 3:09.57, the British women's team
in the 4x200 freestyle with 7:49.11.
</P>
<P>
The championships records were set by Sarah Poewe from South
Africa in the women's 50-meter breaststroke with 30.66, Brendon
Dedekind also from South Africa in the men's 50-meter breaststroke
with 27.13 and American Jenny Thompson in the women's 100-meter
freestyle with 52.92.
</P>
<P>
China's Hao Ping finished second in the women's 50-meter
breaststroke with 31.22 while the Chinese women's team won the
bronze in the 4x200 freestyle with 7.52.70.
</P>
<P>
The four-day championships has already broken many records:
participating athletes of more than 540 and teams of over 75, and
accredited media representatives.
</P>
<P>
China has fielded a team of 20 swimmers, including men's 100-
and 200-meter medley ace Xie Xufeng, and women's 100-meter
freestyle champion Yang Yu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
