<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Japanese Red Army Members Expelled to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon evicted four Japanese Red
Army members to Jordan Friday when their political asylum request
was turned down.
</P>
<P>
Only one member of the group, 51-year-old Kozo Okamoto, is
permitted to stay in Lebanon, announced the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Four members were sent to Amman from Beirut via a Middle East
Airline flight on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The five Japanese are wanted in Japan on international terrorism
charges and face possible execution if found guilty, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which does not have an extradition agreement with
Lebanon, had informally sought the extradition of the five since
they were arrested in Lebanon on February 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Beirut has turned down Tokyo's request because Lebanese law
stipulates that they must first serve their sentences before any
extradition demand can be examined. 
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Kozo Okamoto, Masao Adachi, 59, Kazuo Tohira, 46,
Harowo Wako, 50, and Mariko Yamamoto, 59, were each sentenced to 42
months in prison for forging documents, using false passports and
residing in Lebanon illegally.
</P>
<P>
They finished their three year of imprisonment term last week
and asked for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid extradition, Adachi recently married a
Lebanese woman and converted to Greek Orthodox Christianity.
Okamoto and two others converted to Islam.
</P>
<P>
Okamoto was the sole surviving perpetrator of the 1972 attack on
Israel's Ben Gurion Airport in that left 26 people dead. The
attack was organized by the Japanese Red Army and the Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
He was sentenced to life imprisonment in Israel but was freed
along with 1,150 Palestinians in a swap for Israeli soldiers in
1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
