<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Want Chechen Campaign Continued, Putin Will Win: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Most Russians expect that the
federal troops should continue the military campaign in the
breakaway republic of Chechnya and Russian acting President
Vladimir Putin will win the upcoming presidential race, shows a
latest poll in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-three percent of Russians, 3 percent more than a month
ago, think that the Chechen campaign must be pursued to an end.
This is the result of a representative poll among 1,600 adult
Russians, conducted by the All-Russian Public Opinion Survey
Center on March 13 following a similar survey in mid-February,
said the Interfax news agency Friday.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of those, who favor an end to the hostilities
and the start of negotiations with the Chechen leadership, slipped
from 22 percent in February to 19 percent in March, according to
the survey.
</P>
<P>
Even if the federal troops suffer greater losses in the
campaign, 61 percent of the respondents against 59 percent in
February believe that the offensive should be continued, while 9
percent do not share this position and another 18 percent declined
to answer (8 and 22 percent last month respectively).
</P>
<P>
Sixty-three percent of the answers (60 percent in February) do
not recognize Aslan Maskhadov as legitimate president of Chechnya,
with 15 percent (17 percent in the previous month) admitting him.
</P>
<P>
In 56 percent of the respondents' opinions, Chechnya should be
made a special federal territory not enjoying the full rights of a
Russia region.
</P>
<P>
As many as the same percent of the voters (47 percent in
February) agree that Chechnya must be governed directly by Moscow,
while 25 percent of the poll participants disagree (30 percent
last month).
</P>
<P>
The public opinion center also forecasts no surprises in the
March 26 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
"The main sensation is that no sensations are expected," said
director of the center Yuri Levada. "The people have made their
choice. The main curiosity is what will happen next and what kind
of policy we will have," he said.
</P>
<P>
Levada's deputy, Alexei Grazhdankin, described the election
campaign as "rather dull" because "only 6 percent of voters
planning to take part in the elections have not made up their
minds."
</P>
<P>
Regardless of acting President Vladimir Putin's ratings
fluctuations, it is possible that he will be elected president of
Russia, Grazhdankin said.
</P>
<P>
"Putin's rating makes it possible for him to win the elections
in the first round. But even if we allow for a second round, Putin
would receive the support of two thirds of voters if his rival was
(the Communist leader) Gennady Zyuganov, and three fourths of the
votes if his rival was (liberal economist) Grigory Yavlinsky,"
Grazhdankin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Colombian Policemen Kidnapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Four Colombian policemen have been
kidnapped, presumably by members of some guerrilla organization in
the department of Tolima, the police department said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Police director General Rosso Jose Serrano said that the
kidnapping occurred Thursday in the outskirts of the Fresno
municipality, on the road that communicates the Tolima region with
the coffee growing zone of Caldas.
</P>
<P>
Serrano said that the kidnappers, presumably members of a group
that call themselves "the Bolsheviks," installed an illegal
checkpoint on the road and stopped several vehicles, among them
the one in which a captain, a sergeant, and two agents were
traveling.
</P>
<P>
Tolima police chief Colonel Javier Cifuentes said that the
policemen had been commissioned in an "intelligence" mission to
prevent public disorder in the region. 
</P>
