<HEADLINE> Senior U.N. Emergency Coordinator to Visit Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Carolyn McAskie, the
acting emergency relief coordinator, is expected to lead a six-day
inter-agency mission to the war-torn Angola in a bid to examine
the humanitarian needs of some 1.7 million internally displaced
people in the southern African country, a U.N. spokesman said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference that the
team will set out Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The mission, requested by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
will include officials from the Office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, the World Food Program and the U.N.
Children's Fund, and will undertake a comprehensive assessment of
existing coordination arrangements, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The mission is scheduled to visit Huambo and Kuito, two of the
nation's provincial capitals, where the bulk of internally
displaced persons are located.
</P>
<P>
Angola has been racked since the mid-1960s by a civil war
which has killed nearly one million and displaced millions more.
International relief workers are reported to have difficulties in
gaining access to the needy people, who have been internally
displaced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
