<DOCNO> XIE20000317.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meet N. Irish Leader to Push Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Clinton was welcoming Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern to the
White House for a St. Patrick's Day ceremony and later was meeting
with pro-Britain Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble; Sinn
Fein's leader Gerry Adams; John Hume, the Social Democratic Party
leader.
</P>
<P>
Trimble told a press conference at the National Press Club that
he is expected to have "direct contact" with the republican
leadership.
</P>
<P>
"The good news about Ireland is that even though the
institutions have been taken down over the difference between the
parties on decommissioning, no-one wants to go back to the way it
was or give up the peace process," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"We need to restore a process that will eventually lead to all
the requirements of the Good Friday Accord being observed,"
Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said he expects eventual restoration of the suspended
government, but the Irish Republic Army (IRA) must first provide
concrete evidence they will begin decommissioning weapons, or
disarming.
</P>
<P>
"Decommissioning would not be important if there was not a
genuine commitment to peaceful means," Trimble added. "And
decommissioning was always seen as just being part of a process
that would, at the end of the day, involve the elimination not
just of weapons of but of paramilitary organizations themselves."
</P>
<P>
"It is only because -- not only because, but it's largely
because over the years the paramilitaries have shown no sign of
dismantling, no sign of ending permanently their terrorist
campaign, that there has come to be such a focus on the question
of weapons decommissioning," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, Clinton urged leaders of major parties to
make concessions in order to restore the province's coalition
government and avoid a renewal of violence.
</P>
<P>
"Life is fleeting and opportunities come and go. We have the
chance of a lifetime. Whatever the differences, it's not worth
another life, not one. It's not worth another day's delay,"
Clinton told a gala dinner attended by Adams and Trimble.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the statement before holding five separate
meetings Friday and hosting a St. Patrick's Day reception at the
White House. Thursday's dinner was hosted by the America Ireland
Fund and joined by more than 1,000 guests.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told the guests that he was proud of the supporting
role he had played in the peace process, adding that the cease-
fires now are measured in years, not weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I must confess as your friend that I still do not know the
answers," he said, expressing his regrets that the peace process
is in a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told a
regular briefing that the administration did not expect any
breakthrough during Friday's meetings.
</P>
<P>
"I'd say that this is more than just courtesy, but I also don't
anticipate any breakthrough. There are discussions scheduled for
when they return home, and they will continue to try to find a way
through to implementing the Good Friday accords," Lockhart added.
</P>
<P>
The Good Friday accords was signed by the parties involved in
the future of the British province of Northern Ireland in 1998.
The peace process runs into an impasse after the Irish Republic
Army (IRA) refused to disarm and Britain suspended the self-rule
in the province in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
