<HEADLINE> Team in DRC Completes Visits to Four Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. technical
assessment team in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has
completed trips to three of the four sites where peace-keeping
troops will eventually be based, a U.N. spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, the U.N. spokesman, told a press conference here
that the team visited Mbuji-Mayi, Kanagnga and Mbandaka between
Tuesday and Thursday, and they are expected to visit Matadi, the
fourth site, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Deployment of the 5,500 military personnel is expected to
take from four to six months, which means that the mission will be
deployed by the end of June at the earliest," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. under-secretary-general for peace-keeping operations,
Bernard Miyet, has just completed a visit to the Central African
country. Miyet is expected to brief the Security Council on the
proposed mission on the DRC on March 28.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council heeded the recommendation by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to remarkably expand the U.N. peace-
keeping presence in DRC in order to put an end to the many-sided
conflict on the African continent, which involves at least six
African nations.  
