<HEADLINE> U.N. Humanitarian Envoy Provides Briefing on Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Ross Mountain, the U.N.
special humanitarian envoy to Mozambique, is back in Geneva Friday,
where he updated donor countries on the outcome of his mission,
Fred Eckhard, the U.N. spokesman, said here.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told a press conference that the U.N. envoy is
expected to give a news conference in Geneva on what he found
during his visit to the southern African country, ravaged by the
worst floods in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
As of Friday, 463,000 people who lost their homes in
Mozambique are being cared for in 121 centers, Eckhard said,
adding that contributions reported to the Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs for the floods now total 119
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The transitional appeal for Mozambique, which will cover a
six-month period and address reconstruction needs, is expected to
be launched next week," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan joined the
U.N. agencies once again in calling for massive aid to Mozambique,
saying that the flooding in the Southern African country was "all
the more tragic" because the nation was considered an African
success story over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief's call coincided with the announcement by the
Rome-based U.N. World Food Program (WFP) to prepare a second
appeal to help Mozambican flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, concerned over the worsening flooding
situation in Mozambique, has responded with strengthened efforts
to seek more funds, helicopters for the Southern African country
in a bid to assist Maputo in fighting against the flooding.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique had recovered from a civil war, which broke out
shortly after its independence fro Portugal in 1975. The United
Nations sent a peace-keeping force into the country to cement a
1992 truce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
