<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore is
better than Texas Governor George W. Bush in handling the country'
s economy, a poll said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gore, who decided last summer to focus more heavily on his
economic role in the Clinton administration, has convinced the
public that he can keep the strong economy going, said the survey
conducted by Republican and Democratic pollsters.
</P>
<P>
But overall, the survey showed that Bush had a 48 percent lead
over Gore's 44 percent in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Gore has closed his gap with Bush a bit among male voters,
largely on their increased confidence in his ability to handle the
economy, said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake.
</P>
<P>
The poll indicates advantages for Republican Bush in concerns
about the nation's moral climate.
</P>
<P>
Gore and Bush are close among women, with Gore having a level
of support that is 4 points higher.
</P>
<P>
The poll also indicated Bush and Gore are about even in the
public view on many issues and candidate qualities.
</P>
<P>
Likely voters consider moral values, improving education,
strengthening Social Security and improving health care as top
issues. 
</P>
