<HEADLINE> Hostages Released in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 32 staff members of the
multi-national oil firm Shell were released on Friday after being
held hostage for five days by Nigerian youths in the country's
Niger delta region.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman for Shell, the protesters freed their
workers after hard negotiations involving local officials and
community leaders.
</P>
<P>
The youths stormed the Utorogu, a Shell gas plant near
Nigeria's oil town of Warri, on Monday morning, demanding the
company to improve a local road.
</P>
<P>
The gas plant, which feeds power plants in southern Nigeria,
still remains closed.
</P>
<P>
Hostage taking and acts of sabotage are frequent in the Niger
delta region, where local communities feel they have been
exploited by foreign oil companies and neglected by successive
Nigerian federal governments.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's civil government took office last year with a pledge
to end the disorder and poverty in the delta. The bill on
developing the area is among the first batch of bills President
Olusegun Obasanjo sent to the country's top legislature for
approval. 
</P>
