<HEADLINE> Koehler: IMF Should Concentrate on Preventing Economic Crises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Horst Koehler,
chosen to head the International Monetary Fund (IMF), said Friday
the global lender must emphasize preventing future financial
crises by monitoring countries' economies more closely.
</P>
<P>
Koehler also said he was ready for discussions with
congressional and other critics who say the IMF has become too
expensive, powerful and secretive and want to scale down its
operations.
</P>
<P>
Koehler, 57, now head of the European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development, said at his debut news conference at the IMF
headquarters that he expected the IMF's 24 executive directors to
formally select him as managing director next week to succeed
Michel Camdessus, who stepped down in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Wearing a red badge marked "visitor," Koehler said he felt "it
is now more important for me to listen carefully before making any
specific statements on the role of the fund, listen to IMF
shareholders, to its staff but also to outside experts."
</P>
<P>
However, in the future, he said, the IMF should "focus even
more on crisis prevention and we should make the best use of the
strength of this institution" by providing countries with good
advice on sound economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Koehler said he was "open to discussion and dialogue with the U.
S. congress about reforms."
</P>
<P>
He also said he would hold similar talks with nongovernmental
organizations such as development and environmental groups because
"there is an obligation to explain" IMF policies. Some of these
groups have threatened to disrupt the meetings next month of the
IMF and the World Bank. Koehler said he did not know if he would
be in office in time for these meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
