<HEADLINE> British Beef to be Sold again on German Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 BERLIN, March 17 (Xinhua)-- British beef can be sold again on
the German market despite the BSE-problem insolvable.
</P>
<P>
The upper house of the German parliament, the Bundesrat, had
lifted a national import ban on British beef Friday in Bonn. The
European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union welcomed the decision of the German Bundesrat.
</P>
<P>
But British beef must be clearly labeled to protect consumers
from the possible risks of mad cow disease, or bovine spongiform
encephalopathy (BSE).
</P>
<P>
Britain also welcomed the lifting of the ban on British beef
through the German Bundesrat. British Farm Secretary Nick Brown
said London hoped that German consumers could be enjoy the good
quality of British beef again.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and his cabinet approved
earlier lifting Germany's ban on British beef imports.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has already lifted a ban on British beef
exports last August 1. The ban had been imposed in 1996 after the
BSE disease broke out which was believed to cause a brain disease
in humans. But France and Germany had still kept national bans on
British beef despite of the EU's ruling.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France were the only EU member nations which
refused to comply with the EU agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
