<HEADLINE> Mexican Government Defends Trade Accord with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario Green dismissed criticisms
from leftist opposition and from organizations that consider the
pact damages Mexican interests.
</P>
<P>
Green said that all the productive sectors of the country were
consulted during the process of the trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister admitted that "an agreement is a
commitment" that will not satisfy every one of the parts.
</P>
<P>
She said that the trade pact will benefit Mexico and that the
ratification of the text in the European parliaments confirms that
the members of the EU think that it will benefit them in the
immediate future."
</P>
<P>
The discussion of the approval in the Senate of the Republic
will conclude before Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo signs the
agreement in Portugal on March 23.
</P>
<P>
The free trade agreement between Mexico and the European Union
will go in force July 1 of this year and will mean the immediate
liberation of tariffs for 47 percent of the Mexican industrial
products and 82 percent for the European commodities.
</P>
<P>
When fully implemented, the agreement will cover 100 percent of
Mexico-EU trade in industrial products, 99.5 percent of trade in
the fisheries sector and 62 percent of trade in agricultural
products.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament on Thursday overwhelmingly approved the
free trade deal with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Mexico and the EU completed talks last November on the free-
trade agreement which the EU hopes will put European companies on
a more equal footing in the Mexican market with U.S. and Canadian
rivals which have benefited from the 1994 North American Free
Trade Agreement (NAFTA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
