<HEADLINE> Clinton Says to Try Reduce Tension on South Asia Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON,March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Friday that he hoped to use his trip to South Asia to
reduce tension between India and Pakistan and rekindle the
relationship between the United States and India.
</P>
<P>
"I want to do what I can to reduce tensions on the Indian
subcontinent, to reduce the likelihood of weapons proliferation
and the likelihood of conflict," Clinton told reporters in the
Oval House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton leaves for South Asia on Saturday and stops initially
in Bangladesh. Then he will spend five days in India and conclude
the trip with a brief stop in Pakistan where he will be the first
U.S. president to visit since 1969.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has already made clear that nuclear-armed India and
Pakistan must exercise military and diplomatic restraint if they
expect good relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I will make clear our view that a nuclear-future is a
dangerous future for them and for the world," he said earlier.
</P>
<P>
He said he would improve relationship with India through this
long overdue visit, the last been the one by former President
Jimmy Carter 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We have a lot of things we can do together, a lot of mutual
interests. obviously what I hope to do first is to rekindle the
relationship between the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about his trip to Pakistan, Clinton said he would
support "the restoration of democratic rule in Pakistan, and to
continue our cooperation with them against terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said he was looking forward to a stop in
Bangladesh, saying: "I have seen a lot of the initiatives taken in
Bangladesh, particularly for the empowerment of poor people, that
I think are important there and throughout the world." 
</P>
