<HEADLINE> Russia Expresses Dissatisfaction Over Kosovo Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov on Friday expressed dissatisfaction over the international
peacekeeping operation in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, saying
the implementation of UN Security Council Resolution No. 1244 on
Kosovo is "far away from satisfaction".
</P>
<P>
However, it would be "impossible and unrealistic" for Russia to
revise unilaterally its role in the peacekeeping operation in
Kosovo, Ivanov said at a State Duma (the lower house of parliament)
meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia, which has 3,600 servicemen in its contingent in
Kosovo, has only one way to influence the situation positively,
namely "through the UN Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Ivanov admitted that Russia has often been isolated in that
body, but still capable of defending its position. China has
shared Russia's position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
There are no other levers of influence in the Security Council
available to Russia, "but we have the Council's resolution and we
can insist on its implementation," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev also
told the parliament that the U.N. Security Council Resolution 1244
is being "unsatisfactorily" enforced.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation in the province is growing worse and
could "lead to new armed clashes" within two to three months.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Moscow is determined to keep its peacekeepers in
Kosovo from being drawn into any local armed conflicts, vowed
Sergeyev.
</P>
<P>
He railed at NATO's Kosovo Force (KFOR). More recalcitrant
ethnic Albanian nationalists have become increasingly active with
KFOR's "tacit consent," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and its closer allies in NATO are continuing
to implement plans to strengthen their military and political
presence in Kosovo and the Balkans as a whole," noted Sergeyev,
charging the West of planning to draw Russian peacekeepers into
armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"We, in turn, have prepared our own plans to counter a possible
escalation of the situation in the Balkans," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
