<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil-Producing Countries Urged to Increase Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
urged Friday oil-producing countries to make a "substantial
production increase", big enough to rebuild depleted reserves and
bring down high oil prices.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Clinton said oil producers deserve "a fair
return" that would avoid the seesawing market that produced 10 U.S.
dollars a barrel in 1998 and more than triple that price today, 14
months later.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he had talked with Saudi Arabia's King Fahd about
the need to stabilize oil prices at levels that satisfy both
producing and consuming nations. Saudi Arabia already has said it
favors increasing production.
</P>
<P>
"I think everybody's struggling now to find a consensus,"
Clinton told reporters when asked about the high oil and gasoline
prices Friday during an meeting on gun control issues.
</P>
<P>
Oil ministers from the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC), are expected at a meeting March 27 to agree to
additional production, but no one knows how much or how soon. The
OPEC producers cut production by 4.3 million barrels a day in late
1998 and early 1999, to force prices up from below 10 dollars a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
While those prices were too low, current prices, ranging as
high as 34 dollars a barrel in recent weeks, "have gone way too
high" and threaten to destabilize the world economy, said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"They've got to find the right balance," he said of the OPEC
producers, although adding that the decision on how much more oil
to pump is "for them to make."
</P>
<P>
There has been growing pressure from Congress for the Clinton
administration to order a drawdown of oil from the government's
emergency petroleum reserve, and administration officials have
said that option remains "on the table."
</P>
<P>
But as recently as Wednesday, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
said he would recommend against using the reserve oil of more than
560 million barrels, which is supposed to be there to respond to
emergency supply disruptions and not to influence prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
